00:01:08.740 --> 00:01:11.065
OK, have you got this handout?

00:01:11.065 --> 00:01:12.805
It deals with two topics.

00:01:16.150 --> 00:01:26.350
First of all, let me
set the framework.

00:01:26.350 --> 00:01:31.600
I argued that modernism was
an existential preoccupation

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:37.420
with the present, given that
the present was sufficiently

00:01:37.420 --> 00:01:46.810
rich and exploratory and
creative, and absolutely devoid

00:01:46.810 --> 00:01:49.670
of the past.

00:01:49.670 --> 00:01:52.240
He didn't speculate
much about the future,

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:57.650
arguing that if you take care
of your existence at the moment,

00:01:57.650 --> 00:02:03.720
particularly if you are on
the verge of a new world,

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:06.540
prediction was not necessary.

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:09.630
Curiously enough, the
past was not necessarily

00:02:09.630 --> 00:02:13.500
intellectually either.

00:02:13.500 --> 00:02:17.500
This is just not because
of the absence of culture.

00:02:17.500 --> 00:02:19.670
This is largely a
European movement

00:02:19.670 --> 00:02:24.120
to which people have been
thinking and philosophizing

00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:28.130
about architecture and urbanism
for thousands of years.

00:02:31.050 --> 00:02:39.350
So the hermetic phenomenon of
modernism led me to explore,

00:02:39.350 --> 00:02:46.490
in last week's lecture,
in the postmodern version

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:54.200
of trying to use
devices such as geometry

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:59.600
to enhance the future
change, accepting

00:02:59.600 --> 00:03:05.660
that the future implies change.

00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:12.860
It's difficult to precisely
be clear about to the extent

00:03:12.860 --> 00:03:16.520
that stochastic methods
enable one to know something

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:17.315
about the future.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:22.910
Together with that
was a preoccupation

00:03:22.910 --> 00:03:29.390
with the immensely larger
notion of the present,

00:03:29.390 --> 00:03:31.730
much more interested
in the complexity

00:03:31.730 --> 00:03:34.910
of the understanding
of the present

00:03:34.910 --> 00:03:39.080
than modernism thought of.

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:44.090
For Corbusier, the
relegation of the plane

00:03:44.090 --> 00:03:48.320
of buildings in the
city to greenspace

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:53.840
didn't ask a question about
the institutional framework

00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:57.920
for creating or
maintaining such a system.

00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:00.800
There were no questions
about what security

00:04:00.800 --> 00:04:04.250
would be like in a
green plane of a city

00:04:04.250 --> 00:04:06.230
with no local monitoring.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:20.670
Modernism was [? pre-crime, ?]
pre the maleability of social

00:04:20.670 --> 00:04:24.990
institutions to allow people
to take part in decisions

00:04:24.990 --> 00:04:27.870
in a democracy.

00:04:27.870 --> 00:04:35.220
It was apolitical, so Corbusier
could shift his correct plan

00:04:35.220 --> 00:04:44.800
from corporate capitalism
to colonial Algiers

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:49.540
to syndicalist Moscow, making
plans for each of these,

00:04:49.540 --> 00:04:55.990
given the geometric
formations would be absolute.

00:04:55.990 --> 00:04:59.920
What I want to try to do
today to deal with the past.

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:08.170
If we are now blessed with axes
both forward and backwards,

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:14.820
we have a much richer and
even more difficult to

00:05:14.820 --> 00:05:20.910
deal with urban existence.

00:05:20.910 --> 00:05:28.990
And we try to make the world
of the past more complex.

00:05:28.990 --> 00:05:33.420
It divides itself into
two systems of knowledge--

00:05:33.420 --> 00:05:35.730
history and memory.

00:05:35.730 --> 00:05:39.160
I'll spend a bit
of time with each,

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:42.240
and try to give you some
accounting of the difference

00:05:42.240 --> 00:05:47.550
between history and memory, and
spend a lot more time on memory

00:05:47.550 --> 00:05:48.420
than on history.

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:55.810
The first page of
the handout deals

00:05:55.810 --> 00:06:07.330
with the list of 10 different
attitudes and practices

00:06:07.330 --> 00:06:08.400
regarding the past.

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:15.670
You can add number 11,
which I haven't, which

00:06:15.670 --> 00:06:22.585
I've since added, which deals
with remembering at a distance.

00:06:28.940 --> 00:06:31.850
This phenomenon of
remembering at a distance

00:06:31.850 --> 00:06:36.860
has become much more
available to us.

00:06:36.860 --> 00:06:41.090
It was available to
the Jews in 70 AD when

00:06:41.090 --> 00:06:48.380
they left the last temple
and went into the diaspora,

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:53.960
but remembered Jerusalem in
their prayers every Passover,

00:06:53.960 --> 00:06:58.910
even today, returning
to Jerusalem

00:06:58.910 --> 00:07:00.440
being part of the mantra.

00:07:04.110 --> 00:07:06.630
Remembering at a
distance is also

00:07:06.630 --> 00:07:11.430
possible in the interpretation
of Christianity, which I gave,

00:07:11.430 --> 00:07:20.340
when Jesus in the forequarter
of the second Jewish temple

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:25.530
says the temple will be
destroyed in a number of years.

00:07:25.530 --> 00:07:28.890
He says to his
disciples, remember

00:07:28.890 --> 00:07:35.370
that my body will be your
temple, referring in some ways

00:07:35.370 --> 00:07:41.250
to the canonical version
of Christianity which

00:07:41.250 --> 00:07:48.330
interprets Christ's body in the
mass through blood and bread.

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:54.626
Still today, it's remembering
at a distance [INAUDIBLE]..

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:03.020
So given that we
have an increase

00:08:03.020 --> 00:08:07.430
in the diasporas of the
world through migration,

00:08:07.430 --> 00:08:11.760
we just had an incident
this month in Boston,

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:17.720
which deals with the
phenomenologically difficult

00:08:17.720 --> 00:08:21.050
notion of interpreting
allegiance

00:08:21.050 --> 00:08:22.640
through after migration.

00:08:26.690 --> 00:08:31.180
This is a contemporary
problem, and it

00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:40.450
makes urbanism very
much more difficult,

00:08:40.450 --> 00:08:44.850
given conventional
notions of allegiance

00:08:44.850 --> 00:08:49.890
to city, to state, to nation.

00:08:49.890 --> 00:08:54.030
I had a thesis two years
ago, done by a Korean woman

00:08:54.030 --> 00:08:59.220
from Los Angeles, who analyzed
the-- do you know the thesis.

00:08:59.220 --> 00:09:00.530
AUDIENCE: You told me about it.

00:09:00.530 --> 00:09:01.050
JULIAN BEINART: Oh, did I?

00:09:01.050 --> 00:09:01.740
I'm sorry.

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:08.520
We analyzed the status
of immigrant groups

00:09:08.520 --> 00:09:12.660
in Los Angeles, where I think
one third of the population

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:19.710
are non-American, or in the
process of becoming American.

00:09:19.710 --> 00:09:24.810
For them, there
was no city center

00:09:24.810 --> 00:09:28.560
to give allegiance to as in
the traditional spatial form

00:09:28.560 --> 00:09:30.300
of the city.

00:09:30.300 --> 00:09:34.830
So she took upon herself
to utilize the emerging

00:09:34.830 --> 00:09:37.620
underground public
transportation

00:09:37.620 --> 00:09:42.240
system as a dispersed
form of identity

00:09:42.240 --> 00:09:50.670
for a migrated population, who
are generally poorer, anyway.

00:09:50.670 --> 00:09:52.770
I don't want to get on to that.

00:09:52.770 --> 00:09:58.900
Let me tell you the sequence
of what we're going to do.

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:01.440
And we go briefly
through this list,

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:04.710
give you some
indications of examples,

00:10:04.710 --> 00:10:15.880
and then going to
go to number 6--

00:10:15.880 --> 00:10:20.520
no, number 8 and 9
to analyze briefly

00:10:20.520 --> 00:10:25.200
the ideas of two urban
theorists of recent time, Aldo

00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:30.270
Rossi, the Italian who won
the Prtizker Prize stupidly.

00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:37.960
He wasn't stupid, but the
Pritzker committee was stupid.

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:41.490
He's a man who wrote a very
good book called Architecture

00:10:41.490 --> 00:10:46.560
of the City as a theorist
who taught it in Switzerland,

00:10:46.560 --> 00:10:52.230
but his buildings are
sacrilegiously bad

00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:54.600
and very few.

00:10:54.600 --> 00:10:56.760
And seeing the
Pritzker prizes still

00:10:56.760 --> 00:11:03.540
reward people not for theory,
but for practice, it's a shame.

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:09.240
This shows how misguided
architectural criticism is.

00:11:12.570 --> 00:11:14.580
And the other is
Leon Krier, whom

00:11:14.580 --> 00:11:18.960
I've chosen as an arch
example of classicism

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:22.020
as a method of dealing
with the present

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:23.520
through the lens of the past.

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:31.680
For the rest, I will
choose examples and slide

00:11:31.680 --> 00:11:34.800
which indicate examples
from all of this list.

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:37.320
Let me just go through
the list very briefly.

00:11:40.890 --> 00:11:44.220
You can reshape as before.

00:11:44.220 --> 00:11:47.070
The ghetto in Warsaw
was built much

00:11:47.070 --> 00:11:49.680
like the version
of the ghetto which

00:11:49.680 --> 00:11:56.340
the Jews revolted in at the
end of the '39, '45 war.

00:11:56.340 --> 00:12:00.210
So for parts of Bologna--

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:02.850
you can build anew.

00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:08.070
One of the best examples
is the rebuilding

00:12:08.070 --> 00:12:10.860
of the center of
Rotterdam, and I there's

00:12:10.860 --> 00:12:18.720
an illustration of
both in the text.

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:21.840
Number 3, make an open
system to allow memory

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:24.510
to be achieved over time.

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:29.130
This is the example of the
Free University in Berlin.

00:12:29.130 --> 00:12:33.630
We don't do anything
to mark the past.

00:12:33.630 --> 00:12:35.760
We leave it open to
the community who

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:41.800
lives there to create their own
monuments, their own memories,

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:46.260
their own museums, their own
patterns, their own geometries.

00:12:46.260 --> 00:12:50.190
If of the past, good enough.

00:12:50.190 --> 00:12:53.610
If not of the past,
but existentially only

00:12:53.610 --> 00:12:55.440
of the present, good enough.

00:13:00.120 --> 00:13:07.320
There is a early
electronic website.

00:13:07.320 --> 00:13:12.120
[INAUDIBLE] was in my class,
in an advanced version

00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:14.790
of this class, when
he was a student here

00:13:14.790 --> 00:13:16.500
doing his doctorate.

00:13:16.500 --> 00:13:20.370
He unearthed an
electronic program

00:13:20.370 --> 00:13:22.680
which people could join.

00:13:22.680 --> 00:13:27.660
There was a site somewhere,
nowhere, electronically,

00:13:27.660 --> 00:13:31.890
and people could occupy
space systematically

00:13:31.890 --> 00:13:37.050
in this virtual space.

00:13:37.050 --> 00:13:39.990
After a time, the
historical society

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:43.230
grew up in this virtual space.

00:13:43.230 --> 00:13:48.960
I imagine the need to program
your life in sequence.

00:13:52.390 --> 00:13:57.700
Freud said something-- well,
I'll quote Freud in a minute.

00:13:57.700 --> 00:14:01.460
Let's rather stick
to my program.

00:14:01.460 --> 00:14:06.070
So easy to jump
from one to another.

00:14:06.070 --> 00:14:08.380
And before, leave
all your fragments,

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:09.400
but add a new program.

00:14:12.780 --> 00:14:18.120
This plays on the duality
of meaning between a remnant

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:22.710
of the past and the present.

00:14:22.710 --> 00:14:25.620
Church Court is a good example.

00:14:25.620 --> 00:14:29.700
Church Court has dual
meaning, or at least

00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:31.800
pertains to a dual meaning.

00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:34.230
You know what Church Court is.

00:14:34.230 --> 00:14:37.830
This is just the building
just across the bridge

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:38.910
on Beacon Street.

00:14:42.250 --> 00:14:45.190
The fragments of the
church are maintained,

00:14:45.190 --> 00:14:48.250
and a new apartment
building is added to it.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:55.450
Freud said something
extraordinary.

00:14:55.450 --> 00:14:57.360
I can't find the quotation here.

00:15:00.310 --> 00:15:04.570
But Freud says that it is
impossible to represent

00:15:04.570 --> 00:15:10.450
the same content pictorially
in the same image.

00:15:10.450 --> 00:15:13.360
If you want to share how
Rome has grown over time,

00:15:13.360 --> 00:15:16.440
you have to
juxtapose situations.

00:15:19.080 --> 00:15:24.150
You cannot spatially have a
unique meaning which has both

00:15:24.150 --> 00:15:27.000
ingredients in it
according to Freud.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:31.050
Therefore, it says, to
represent mental processes

00:15:31.050 --> 00:15:34.890
through pictorially
image is a waste of time,

00:15:34.890 --> 00:15:39.870
for it is implying that
in our mental mechanism

00:15:39.870 --> 00:15:43.590
we are able to
simultaneously think

00:15:43.590 --> 00:15:49.020
of our mother and our
girlfriend simultaneously.

00:15:49.020 --> 00:15:54.950
But we cannot depict spatial
contexts simultaneously.

00:15:54.950 --> 00:16:00.600
Now, juxtaposing the two
formal elements of Church Court

00:16:00.600 --> 00:16:02.370
is a method.

00:16:02.370 --> 00:16:06.840
A Freudian-- not Freudian,
it's a pretty pedantic method

00:16:06.840 --> 00:16:11.040
of getting meaning from
the past and associating

00:16:11.040 --> 00:16:12.450
with meaning with the present.

00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:14.820
There was a church here.

00:16:14.820 --> 00:16:17.350
That is a memory function.

00:16:17.350 --> 00:16:19.350
There is now a building now.

00:16:19.350 --> 00:16:20.310
This is modern.

00:16:20.310 --> 00:16:22.850
There's no memory
yet attached to it.

00:16:22.850 --> 00:16:28.560
So in the space-time continuum,
you're representing meanings

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:30.630
at different times.

00:16:30.630 --> 00:16:34.590
You are also marking
urbanisticlly the fact

00:16:34.590 --> 00:16:37.710
that on that corner,
there was a church,

00:16:37.710 --> 00:16:39.600
and there was a
community of people

00:16:39.600 --> 00:16:44.130
who worshipped in the
Back Bay prior to them

00:16:44.130 --> 00:16:47.650
immigrating, and leaving
the need for the Back Bay

00:16:47.650 --> 00:16:51.540
to produce only fewer churches.

00:16:51.540 --> 00:16:54.600
You can play around with this
game as long as you want to.

00:16:54.600 --> 00:16:57.360
I'll give you a
number of examples

00:16:57.360 --> 00:17:00.410
of the obscurity of this game.

00:17:00.410 --> 00:17:07.500
And architects at times, like
Peter Eisenman and others,

00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:08.760
have played around.

00:17:08.760 --> 00:17:14.000
In fact the Freudian quote
comes from Peter Eisenman's

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.069
introduction to
the Rossi's book.

00:17:22.470 --> 00:17:26.040
Number 5, you can connect
to past urban traces,

00:17:26.040 --> 00:17:28.440
mostly invisible.

00:17:28.440 --> 00:17:31.360
I will show you a
couple of examples,

00:17:31.360 --> 00:17:38.070
one of the Peter Eisenman
studio at Harvard using memory

00:17:38.070 --> 00:17:45.000
to obscure memory traces
from the Midwestern town,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:51.030
and also from the Bicocca
Pirelli Competition in Milan

00:17:51.030 --> 00:17:54.960
and number of years ago, which
all the world's architects took

00:17:54.960 --> 00:17:55.920
part in.

00:17:55.920 --> 00:18:01.650
I will show you the second prize
entry by the firm from Torino

00:18:01.650 --> 00:18:06.360
called Gabetti and
Isola, who tried

00:18:06.360 --> 00:18:11.910
to use traces of
agrarian Roman fields

00:18:11.910 --> 00:18:19.070
in their ecologically
advanced project.

00:18:19.070 --> 00:18:28.920
The trouble with obscure traces
is that they're not present.

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:34.580
Who in the hell can recount a
past history without reference

00:18:34.580 --> 00:18:36.080
to it?

00:18:36.080 --> 00:18:44.700
We did a studio in Taipei
looking at the city center.

00:18:44.700 --> 00:18:49.970
The city center was based
on an old Chinese plan.

00:18:49.970 --> 00:18:54.680
The Japanese came along
and changed the orientation

00:18:54.680 --> 00:18:57.590
of the original plan.

00:18:57.590 --> 00:19:02.720
Some of our students
tried to show this fact.

00:19:02.720 --> 00:19:07.730
But how do you show two
geometries at the same time?

00:19:07.730 --> 00:19:13.400
You can overlay one on another,
but it's difficult to explain.

00:19:13.400 --> 00:19:21.630
But it's not a common,
but a real option.

00:19:21.630 --> 00:19:28.290
Number 6, create new tectonics
based on memory forms.

00:19:28.290 --> 00:19:31.710
The explicit example of
that is the Holocaust Museum

00:19:31.710 --> 00:19:32.920
in Washington.

00:19:32.920 --> 00:19:38.150
Anybody been to the
Holocaust museum?

00:19:38.150 --> 00:19:39.920
Four people.

00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:43.850
I'll quote James Ingo Freed,
the architect who designed it,

00:19:43.850 --> 00:19:49.700
and his references to using
forms borrowed from Auschwtiz--

00:19:49.700 --> 00:19:50.720
Arbeit macht frei.

00:19:53.750 --> 00:20:02.480
And we can judge the quality
of the present experience,

00:20:02.480 --> 00:20:06.980
whose aim is to
teach us to remember

00:20:06.980 --> 00:20:10.100
the events of the past.

00:20:10.100 --> 00:20:15.440
We have a whole panoply of
items, which we use spatially

00:20:15.440 --> 00:20:17.270
to remember the past--

00:20:17.270 --> 00:20:22.220
museums, memorials,
monuments, amongst others.

00:20:24.968 --> 00:20:27.470
I haven't got time
in this class to go

00:20:27.470 --> 00:20:30.290
into the theory of
monuments, but we'll

00:20:30.290 --> 00:20:31.802
talk a bit about them.

00:20:36.890 --> 00:20:42.050
Number 7, build monuments,
memorials, museums.

00:20:42.050 --> 00:20:44.120
Here we have a conflict.

00:20:44.120 --> 00:20:46.220
Robert Musil, the
French philosopher,

00:20:46.220 --> 00:20:50.780
said there is nothing as
invisible as a monument, which

00:20:50.780 --> 00:20:55.610
means that the monument
is made psychologically

00:20:55.610 --> 00:20:58.755
current or non-existent by time.

00:21:01.830 --> 00:21:03.990
Which kid who goes
to Washington,

00:21:03.990 --> 00:21:06.870
and is not told that that's
the Washington Monument,

00:21:06.870 --> 00:21:09.840
knows that it's the
Washington Monument?

00:21:09.840 --> 00:21:11.640
Who even knows who
Washington was?

00:21:15.110 --> 00:21:19.836
Washington's a famous enough
person to be remembered.

00:21:19.836 --> 00:21:23.420
But there's is a town
in Russia, a small town,

00:21:23.420 --> 00:21:28.280
named after Engels, and
one named after Marx.

00:21:28.280 --> 00:21:31.760
And they just they are
undistinguished and not even

00:21:31.760 --> 00:21:35.390
on anybody's map.

00:21:35.390 --> 00:21:37.460
It's not that Marx
is not remembered,

00:21:37.460 --> 00:21:41.210
but the physical manifestation
of him in a monument to him

00:21:41.210 --> 00:21:42.380
is neglected.

00:21:48.980 --> 00:21:51.140
I'll look very briefly--

00:21:51.140 --> 00:21:54.440
although I haven't
got the slides

00:21:54.440 --> 00:21:59.420
to show you because of
time, of a new device

00:21:59.420 --> 00:22:05.960
to take care of the lack
of presence of monuments.

00:22:05.960 --> 00:22:11.510
I advised the United
States Air Force

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:14.690
on the selection of
a site in Washington.

00:22:14.690 --> 00:22:18.980
The United States Air Force
wished to follow the Navy.

00:22:18.980 --> 00:22:22.960
The Navy have-- do you
know the Navy side?

00:22:22.960 --> 00:22:29.740
It's opposite the-- it's a
developer project in downtown,

00:22:29.740 --> 00:22:36.370
which has a semicircular plain,
piazza, on which stands a Navy

00:22:36.370 --> 00:22:39.430
soldier and a map of the world.

00:22:39.430 --> 00:22:43.540
But in order to go
into the museum,

00:22:43.540 --> 00:22:47.440
you have to go into
a developer building.

00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:50.230
And there's a computer
program on which you

00:22:50.230 --> 00:22:53.500
can show your grandchild
a picture of yourself

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:59.950
in the Navy in 1927,
or whatever it is.

00:22:59.950 --> 00:23:02.480
Our clients, the United
States Air Force,

00:23:02.480 --> 00:23:05.410
wished to follow the
same tradition of having

00:23:05.410 --> 00:23:06.750
two items in a museum.

00:23:06.750 --> 00:23:12.010
One is a symbolic fixed
item, and secondly

00:23:12.010 --> 00:23:15.340
an updatable present.

00:23:15.340 --> 00:23:18.790
The first design
by architect who

00:23:18.790 --> 00:23:21.340
happened to be the same
architect as the Holocaust

00:23:21.340 --> 00:23:26.560
museum, Jim Freed, had a plane
with the basement underneath.

00:23:26.560 --> 00:23:30.160
And the basement had all
of the updating mechanisms.

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:36.130
So you could go, but above
it was a huge symbolic item.

00:23:36.130 --> 00:23:42.220
In fact, the memorial was
never built on that site,

00:23:42.220 --> 00:23:48.410
because the Marines argued that
we were too close to the Iwo

00:23:48.410 --> 00:23:54.130
Jima Memorial, which is a
literal evacuation of soldiers

00:23:54.130 --> 00:23:57.440
fighting on an
island in the Orient.

00:23:57.440 --> 00:23:59.980
Anyway, I'm getting
carried away.

00:23:59.980 --> 00:24:01.300
Let's stick to this program.

00:24:08.650 --> 00:24:10.840
Number 8 and number 9--

00:24:10.840 --> 00:24:15.190
number 8 is what I would refer
to in the work of Leon Krier.

00:24:15.190 --> 00:24:22.240
That is the establishment
of European classicism

00:24:22.240 --> 00:24:28.060
as a universal past
independent of time, economy,

00:24:28.060 --> 00:24:34.630
and culture, and therefore
the DNA of the past.

00:24:34.630 --> 00:24:37.520
And therefore, when you work
with the DNA of the past,

00:24:37.520 --> 00:24:42.730
whether it be New Delhi or
in Richmond Terrace in London

00:24:42.730 --> 00:24:45.610
on the river, you are
doing greater things.

00:24:45.610 --> 00:24:52.660
And we'll examine Poundbury,
the town that Leon Krier advised

00:24:52.660 --> 00:24:54.580
Prince Charles on.

00:24:54.580 --> 00:24:57.310
Prince Charles is
very much involved

00:24:57.310 --> 00:25:03.910
in the same classicism
versus modernism argument,

00:25:03.910 --> 00:25:08.440
arguing that London's
been defaced by modernism.

00:25:08.440 --> 00:25:14.960
And here, although I won't
go into it in detail,

00:25:14.960 --> 00:25:20.050
we can add the phenomenon of
new urbanism to this category.

00:25:22.690 --> 00:25:29.815
To use classical
form is a choice.

00:25:32.530 --> 00:25:34.630
It's a stupid choice,
but it's a choice.

00:25:40.390 --> 00:25:45.960
You can't blame people for
disliking modernism when it

00:25:45.960 --> 00:25:47.670
appeared, and for a long time.

00:25:51.210 --> 00:25:59.480
And so include them
in your client group

00:25:59.480 --> 00:26:01.850
as active participants
in your design.

00:26:06.180 --> 00:26:14.775
To use nostalgia as reminiscent
of a lost past is silly.

00:26:17.330 --> 00:26:21.020
The new urbanism doesn't deal
with contemporary issues--

00:26:21.020 --> 00:26:27.390
social equity, overuse of
automobile transportation,

00:26:27.390 --> 00:26:29.330
et cetera, et cetera.

00:26:29.330 --> 00:26:34.460
Diversity of population
in the metropolitan areas

00:26:34.460 --> 00:26:39.990
is a diverse new
urban phenomenon.

00:26:39.990 --> 00:26:44.000
It recreates
nostalgic pasts which

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:50.900
satisfies one much like candy
satisfies a child before he

00:26:50.900 --> 00:26:55.010
grows up and nourishes himself
to believe the candy is not

00:26:55.010 --> 00:26:56.395
good for your body.

00:26:56.395 --> 00:26:58.420
You need to eat decent food.

00:27:01.550 --> 00:27:06.500
Number 9, we can use
Aldo Rossi's argument

00:27:06.500 --> 00:27:12.470
that the city has autonomous
basic forms and places which

00:27:12.470 --> 00:27:16.250
perpetuate themselves--
the idea the locus, which

00:27:16.250 --> 00:27:20.540
I will discuss in a minute.

00:27:20.540 --> 00:27:23.640
Number 10, let context make
the proper associations.

00:27:27.970 --> 00:27:34.160
This is a very appropriate form
taught in architecture schools.

00:27:34.160 --> 00:27:37.300
Rossi argues
absolutely against it.

00:27:37.300 --> 00:27:39.390
He says that
buildings make places,

00:27:39.390 --> 00:27:43.860
and places don't make buildings,
and it's foolish for a building

00:27:43.860 --> 00:27:47.490
to be made up of
adaptations of what

00:27:47.490 --> 00:27:49.740
people have done in the past.

00:27:49.740 --> 00:27:53.430
It's a strange kind of
notion, but there's a politics

00:27:53.430 --> 00:27:58.600
associated with context.

00:27:58.600 --> 00:28:05.310
For instance, the
expanding Spaniards

00:28:05.310 --> 00:28:11.490
destroyed Cusco to a plane
and rebuilt it from scratch.

00:28:11.490 --> 00:28:23.430
They didn't destroy the
Alhambra in post-Islam Spain.

00:28:23.430 --> 00:28:29.580
How is it that the Crusaders
didn't destroy the Dome

00:28:29.580 --> 00:28:31.680
of the Rock or the
Al-Asqa mosque--

00:28:31.680 --> 00:28:33.180
simply put a flag on it?

00:28:36.120 --> 00:28:39.210
Historians have argued that
[INAUDIBLE] be out of respect

00:28:39.210 --> 00:28:41.910
for the quality of
the architecture.

00:28:41.910 --> 00:28:45.420
Now, this assumes a
conquering program having

00:28:45.420 --> 00:28:50.280
a DNA which includes respect.

00:28:50.280 --> 00:28:57.610
AUDIENCE: It also assumes
that [INAUDIBLE] culture

00:28:57.610 --> 00:28:58.608
[INAUDIBLE].

00:29:02.600 --> 00:29:05.060
JULIAN BEINART: Yeah, it
regards colonial cultures,

00:29:05.060 --> 00:29:11.480
as the British [INAUDIBLE]
regarded Indian architecture as

00:29:11.480 --> 00:29:14.990
pathetic, as childish,
as still to be achieved.

00:29:19.080 --> 00:29:21.830
It's a little remarkable,
given the history of Islam

00:29:21.830 --> 00:29:26.990
and the European
center that they

00:29:26.990 --> 00:29:29.830
would regard Islamic
architecture quite

00:29:29.830 --> 00:29:34.550
as automatically as they did.

00:29:34.550 --> 00:29:37.190
Maybe they were worn
out in the [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:37.190 --> 00:29:41.060
They took a hell of a long
time to get rid of Islam.

00:29:41.060 --> 00:29:48.080
They spent all
generations of resources,

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:50.430
and then remembering
it at distance.

00:29:54.230 --> 00:29:57.860
The other example of number
6, other than the Holocaust

00:29:57.860 --> 00:30:02.090
Museum, which comes to mind is
the building you might know.

00:30:02.090 --> 00:30:10.700
In Verona is Carlos
Scarpa's Castelvecchio, one

00:30:10.700 --> 00:30:13.070
of the finest, if
not the finest,

00:30:13.070 --> 00:30:16.580
example of preservation
architecture

00:30:16.580 --> 00:30:20.630
I think in modern times
or in recent times.

00:30:20.630 --> 00:30:23.690
Castelvecchio, which I won't
illustrate-- because I had

00:30:23.690 --> 00:30:26.240
to choose the number of slide.

00:30:26.240 --> 00:30:29.810
I'll try not to share
more than 30 slides--

00:30:29.810 --> 00:30:32.110
60 slides per class.

00:30:32.110 --> 00:30:34.370
And it's very difficult at time.

00:30:34.370 --> 00:30:44.480
Castelvecchio was the
home of a royal family--

00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:47.990
Scaligeri, I think they were.

00:30:47.990 --> 00:30:51.650
In 1925, it was
made into a museum.

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:57.440
In 1956, Carlos Scarpa was
asked to integrate the two.

00:30:57.440 --> 00:31:01.850
And he took the
forms of the past

00:31:01.850 --> 00:31:06.290
and introduced them
to the new building

00:31:06.290 --> 00:31:14.330
in a way which I think Jim Freed
did in the Holocaust Museum.

00:31:14.330 --> 00:31:20.750
But this is difficult work,
and there are not many.

00:31:20.750 --> 00:31:23.190
I'm sure you can think
of examples as well.

00:31:23.190 --> 00:31:25.100
But these are the
two that come to mind

00:31:25.100 --> 00:31:27.740
when I think of this category.

00:31:27.740 --> 00:31:35.375
Let's go to Aldo Rossi briefly,
and then to Leon Krier briefly.

00:31:38.400 --> 00:31:41.640
Rossi uses the past as
a tool for understanding

00:31:41.640 --> 00:31:44.910
the present form of the city.

00:31:44.910 --> 00:31:53.340
For Rossi, past is a continuum
of which we are still a part.

00:31:53.340 --> 00:31:59.370
The past is perpetuated almost
fossilized in the city form,

00:31:59.370 --> 00:32:04.050
even as that form and its
use are constantly changing.

00:32:04.050 --> 00:32:06.140
Primary elements
of the city form

00:32:06.140 --> 00:32:10.860
are perpetuated, through
time creating an autonomous

00:32:10.860 --> 00:32:13.440
system of basic
absolute forms around

00:32:13.440 --> 00:32:18.740
which the city has been,
and continues to be, built.

00:32:18.740 --> 00:32:20.160
It's my abstraction.

00:32:23.690 --> 00:32:26.860
Let's look at a couple
of things that he argues.

00:32:26.860 --> 00:32:28.870
He argues that
there is a dialectic

00:32:28.870 --> 00:32:32.620
between the city as
stones and mortar,

00:32:32.620 --> 00:32:38.470
the actual physical artifact,
and the city of our minds--

00:32:38.470 --> 00:32:41.170
an ideal city that
embodies experiences,

00:32:41.170 --> 00:32:47.650
meaning, and understanding that
is autonomous of time and use.

00:32:47.650 --> 00:32:54.220
Rossi doesn't discuss
memory very much,

00:32:54.220 --> 00:32:56.740
but what he's talking
about are much more

00:32:56.740 --> 00:33:02.620
the attributes of memory than
the attributes of history.

00:33:02.620 --> 00:33:06.430
He refers in his
book to the work

00:33:06.430 --> 00:33:10.810
of Maurice Halbwachs, the
French sociologist who

00:33:10.810 --> 00:33:13.900
wrote a book called The
Collective Memory, which

00:33:13.900 --> 00:33:19.570
I think is one of the
great books of our time.

00:33:19.570 --> 00:33:24.505
And I will refer to
excerpts a bit later.

00:33:27.930 --> 00:33:32.460
Rossi secondly divides
the city timewise

00:33:32.460 --> 00:33:35.760
into primary elements
and dwellings.

00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:39.870
When dwellings are expressions
of ever-changing individual

00:33:39.870 --> 00:33:44.720
will, they constitute the
vernacular architecture

00:33:44.720 --> 00:33:51.720
that is subject to changes
in use, form, and meaning.

00:33:51.720 --> 00:33:53.820
In contrast,
primary elements are

00:33:53.820 --> 00:33:58.170
expressions of collective
will, especially

00:33:58.170 --> 00:34:00.460
the subgroup of monuments.

00:34:00.460 --> 00:34:02.370
So housing is temporary.

00:34:02.370 --> 00:34:13.050
A neighborhood may be
permanent as a primary element.

00:34:13.050 --> 00:34:14.460
I quote from him.

00:34:14.460 --> 00:34:16.654
"A monument's
persistence or permanence

00:34:16.654 --> 00:34:19.659
is a result of its
capacity to constitute

00:34:19.659 --> 00:34:25.440
the city, its history, and
art, its being and memory."

00:34:25.440 --> 00:34:32.760
I've given you a copy
of his project in Padua,

00:34:32.760 --> 00:34:39.880
the Palazzo della
Ragione, which was,

00:34:39.880 --> 00:34:42.690
he argues, an example
of a monument--

00:34:46.139 --> 00:34:47.429
these pages here.

00:34:55.659 --> 00:35:11.410
He goes on to use the term locus
to specify a particular space

00:35:11.410 --> 00:35:13.990
or place in the
city, which forms

00:35:13.990 --> 00:35:16.990
a part of its permanent history.

00:35:16.990 --> 00:35:19.420
And his argument is
the city needs to be

00:35:19.420 --> 00:35:23.140
built on these permanences.

00:35:23.140 --> 00:35:27.400
All new permanences should
be created at the same time

00:35:27.400 --> 00:35:36.440
as maintaining fluidity in
the dispensing of housing.

00:35:42.320 --> 00:35:50.420
He makes the bold statement
that permanence in form

00:35:50.420 --> 00:35:53.930
precedes permanence
in institutions.

00:35:53.930 --> 00:35:57.680
I quote, "The permanence
of a form or its value

00:35:57.680 --> 00:36:01.140
as a reference is entirely
independent on both

00:36:01.140 --> 00:36:04.520
the specific functions
for which it was designed,

00:36:04.520 --> 00:36:07.700
and its [INAUDIBLE]
with a continuity

00:36:07.700 --> 00:36:09.680
of urban institutions.

00:36:09.680 --> 00:36:12.800
For this reason I'm
deliberately emphasizing

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:16.160
the form and the architecture
of the city, rather than

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:19.010
its institutions."

00:36:19.010 --> 00:36:24.710
I mean, primitively, he's
saying that an old building can

00:36:24.710 --> 00:36:28.130
take a different
use without changing

00:36:28.130 --> 00:36:30.840
its form significantly.

00:36:30.840 --> 00:36:35.150
In fact, in the
history-memory distinction,

00:36:35.150 --> 00:36:39.830
he controverts the normal
history-memory relationship

00:36:39.830 --> 00:36:41.180
over time.

00:36:41.180 --> 00:36:45.500
Normally, somebody like
David Lowenthal in the book

00:36:45.500 --> 00:36:48.680
The Past Is a Foreign
Country-- one of the best

00:36:48.680 --> 00:36:54.760
books on architecture
preservation, by the way,

00:36:54.760 --> 00:36:58.960
says that typically,
memory is short-lived,

00:36:58.960 --> 00:37:02.770
and it's replaced by the
permanence of history.

00:37:02.770 --> 00:37:05.020
Rossi reverts the two.

00:37:05.020 --> 00:37:09.220
He says history occurs as
long as a building maintains

00:37:09.220 --> 00:37:10.870
its present use.

00:37:10.870 --> 00:37:16.300
Memory occurs, is instituted
once the use changes.

00:37:16.300 --> 00:37:21.040
These are abstract ideas.

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:26.170
I don't know how much empirical
evidence there is for this,

00:37:26.170 --> 00:37:30.730
or how much Rossi has measured
the permanence of institutions

00:37:30.730 --> 00:37:33.880
as opposed to the
permanence of monuments.

00:37:33.880 --> 00:37:36.550
It doesn't matter.

00:37:36.550 --> 00:37:44.960
Rossi is valuable because
he attracts attention

00:37:44.960 --> 00:37:50.090
to the distinction in value
of certain forms of the city.

00:37:54.280 --> 00:37:56.230
I had an argument
with Kevin Lynch

00:37:56.230 --> 00:37:59.770
about Aldo Rossi saying
this, and I'll just

00:37:59.770 --> 00:38:05.650
quote Lynch from his own writing
about his antagonism to Rossi.

00:38:05.650 --> 00:38:07.300
You can make up your own mind.

00:38:11.590 --> 00:38:15.370
"For Rossi, architecture is an
autonomous discipline, eternal,

00:38:15.370 --> 00:38:19.090
outside of time,
creating form typologies

00:38:19.090 --> 00:38:24.380
which have an independent
existence like Platonic cities.

00:38:24.380 --> 00:38:26.260
The city is a
permanent structure

00:38:26.260 --> 00:38:32.800
through which it remembers
its past, it realizes itself.

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:41.500
These attitudes unfold into
monstrous, seductive flowers.

00:38:41.500 --> 00:38:43.810
They are rooted in
the same false idea

00:38:43.810 --> 00:38:46.210
that man and his
habitat are completely

00:38:46.210 --> 00:38:49.330
separate entities,
linked only, if at all,

00:38:49.330 --> 00:38:54.530
by some mechanical
one-directional causation."

00:38:54.530 --> 00:39:01.990
It's true that Rossi says in his
writing that form has meaning.

00:39:01.990 --> 00:39:03.820
Form creates certain things.

00:39:09.990 --> 00:39:15.420
I'm using [INAUDIBLE]
remembers its past.

00:39:15.420 --> 00:39:19.170
I think I have to give Rossi the
benefit of not being so dumb as

00:39:19.170 --> 00:39:23.640
to believe that
bricks have a brain,

00:39:23.640 --> 00:39:26.170
or stone remembers anything.

00:39:26.170 --> 00:39:31.500
He's doing a syllogistic jump.

00:39:31.500 --> 00:39:34.140
I think syllogistic
is the right word.

00:39:34.140 --> 00:39:37.890
He's assuming that you assume.

00:39:37.890 --> 00:39:42.360
That it's the mental
interpretation of what--

00:39:42.360 --> 00:39:49.840
when Louis Kahn says, and
as he often used to say,

00:39:49.840 --> 00:39:51.145
something makes itself.

00:39:56.110 --> 00:39:59.230
He's not referring to
the mechanical system

00:39:59.230 --> 00:40:01.430
which produces light.

00:40:01.430 --> 00:40:04.030
He's referring to the
human understanding

00:40:04.030 --> 00:40:07.240
of the mechanical system
which produces light.

00:40:07.240 --> 00:40:09.050
He's compressing the idea.

00:40:09.050 --> 00:40:11.920
So I think Kevin is
wrong, and I told him so.

00:40:11.920 --> 00:40:14.650
But he didn't agree with me.

00:40:14.650 --> 00:40:16.900
Poor man, he's not alive
any longer to fight.

00:40:21.850 --> 00:40:24.310
I think you have to
read Rossi now, and make

00:40:24.310 --> 00:40:29.410
an independent decision of
how much that book means.

00:40:29.410 --> 00:40:33.040
I don't think you need to
look at his other books

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:36.970
or to biography of an idea.

00:40:36.970 --> 00:40:40.720
Certainly, don't look
at any of his projects,

00:40:40.720 --> 00:40:42.880
or go to one of them
immediately and be

00:40:42.880 --> 00:40:48.820
appalled by the stupidity
of the thinking.

00:40:48.820 --> 00:40:56.380
Leon Krier is a much more
indomitable character.

00:40:56.380 --> 00:40:59.350
He automatically classifies.

00:40:59.350 --> 00:41:03.820
He makes absolute judgments.

00:41:03.820 --> 00:41:08.320
For him, classical architecture
is the only architecture

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:13.570
that one should contemplate
independent of economy, time,

00:41:13.570 --> 00:41:16.510
culture, et cetera--

00:41:16.510 --> 00:41:17.470
technology.

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:27.220
He also assumes that
equally stark judgments

00:41:27.220 --> 00:41:29.800
can be made between
public buildings

00:41:29.800 --> 00:41:31.990
and private buildings.

00:41:31.990 --> 00:41:37.120
For me, the genius of much
of the complexity of urbanism

00:41:37.120 --> 00:41:43.180
is the overlapping between
public and private entities

00:41:43.180 --> 00:41:44.470
in space.

00:41:44.470 --> 00:41:49.720
If I drove down Memorial
Drive and got to Mount Auburn

00:41:49.720 --> 00:41:52.210
Hospital and looked at
the school across the way,

00:41:52.210 --> 00:41:54.970
which my children went to--

00:41:54.970 --> 00:41:58.580
I had to pay an anomalous
amount of money to that school.

00:41:58.580 --> 00:42:01.630
So therefore, it must
be a private school.

00:42:01.630 --> 00:42:05.780
But it looks like any
school down there.

00:42:05.780 --> 00:42:09.190
If I go down Mount Auburn Street
and come through Watertown,

00:42:09.190 --> 00:42:13.870
there's a classical
facade facing me which

00:42:13.870 --> 00:42:16.180
happens to be a public school.

00:42:16.180 --> 00:42:19.150
In England, a public
is a private school.

00:42:19.150 --> 00:42:22.320
In American, a public
school is a public school.

00:42:24.910 --> 00:42:28.330
What classifications--
I will deal

00:42:28.330 --> 00:42:30.580
with the dichotomy
or the dialectic

00:42:30.580 --> 00:42:36.295
between public and private in
city form in Thursday's class.

00:42:43.670 --> 00:42:46.340
Krier can be criticized
on many levels.

00:42:49.330 --> 00:42:52.230
First of all, the
universality of classicism

00:42:52.230 --> 00:42:56.470
is a political assumption.

00:42:56.470 --> 00:43:02.670
I don't know if Indians and
Gandhi assume classicism

00:43:02.670 --> 00:43:06.560
to be a universal form.

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:10.170
Certainly, I never grew up
in South Africa regarding

00:43:10.170 --> 00:43:13.560
classicism as the
appropriate form

00:43:13.560 --> 00:43:16.705
to satisfy Black
ambitions in South Africa.

00:43:19.400 --> 00:43:24.080
Classicism was always the
form of superior buildings.

00:43:24.080 --> 00:43:28.040
When I went to the low courts,
it had a classical pediment.

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:33.380
When I went to visit a
political friend of mine

00:43:33.380 --> 00:43:37.920
in Johannesburg's
prison, I entered

00:43:37.920 --> 00:43:41.570
under a classical entablature.

00:43:41.570 --> 00:43:45.800
Classicism for me
growing up was associated

00:43:45.800 --> 00:43:54.260
with values which were
eternal and beyond my reality

00:43:54.260 --> 00:43:56.990
as a young person.

00:43:56.990 --> 00:44:01.370
I'm not sure I've ever outgrown
those versions of classicism.

00:44:06.080 --> 00:44:09.695
We have conflicts about
this version of the past.

00:44:12.490 --> 00:44:15.295
I said this before, but the
Boston Symphony always--

00:44:15.295 --> 00:44:17.230
they always used to play--

00:44:17.230 --> 00:44:19.030
I mean, there's a
concert I want to go

00:44:19.030 --> 00:44:24.820
to New York in which Gustavo
Dudamel, the young conductor

00:44:24.820 --> 00:44:28.270
of the Los Angeles
Philharmonic Orchestra,

00:44:28.270 --> 00:44:31.840
is conducting
Bruckner's Number 8.

00:44:31.840 --> 00:44:34.900
If it is a classical
symphony, which

00:44:34.900 --> 00:44:38.440
is all of the overtures
of classicism,

00:44:38.440 --> 00:44:41.230
it's Bruckner Number 8.

00:44:41.230 --> 00:44:44.650
But he is playing
preliminary to it a piece

00:44:44.650 --> 00:44:51.550
by a composer called Corigliano,
a contemporary composer.

00:44:51.550 --> 00:44:55.630
The weight of the
piece is in Bruckner.

00:44:55.630 --> 00:45:00.460
So there is a part of us which
establishes in our culture

00:45:00.460 --> 00:45:05.860
certain values about
the past as absolute,

00:45:05.860 --> 00:45:08.905
and certain values
about the present as OK.

00:45:12.780 --> 00:45:15.540
We are constantly, in
my view of the world,

00:45:15.540 --> 00:45:19.920
balancing these
two problematics,

00:45:19.920 --> 00:45:22.680
coming to a satisfying
conclusions,

00:45:22.680 --> 00:45:27.330
even arguing that Mozart's
piano concertos when he returned

00:45:27.330 --> 00:45:33.570
to Vienna started accounting for
the popular impulse in music.

00:45:33.570 --> 00:45:41.400
And Number 26 is a
wonderful, popular version

00:45:41.400 --> 00:45:44.580
of his earlier piano concerto.

00:45:48.800 --> 00:45:52.895
I don't know how to leave you
with this Leon Krier position.

00:45:52.895 --> 00:45:55.130
I'll show you some slides.

00:45:55.130 --> 00:45:56.390
Look at Poundbury.

00:45:59.570 --> 00:46:03.800
The image I've given you is
from the 1976 La Villette

00:46:03.800 --> 00:46:08.570
competition in which he
won the second Prize.

00:46:08.570 --> 00:46:12.260
I won't show that to
you in the slides.

00:46:12.260 --> 00:46:13.820
It's the last pages of--

00:46:25.930 --> 00:46:29.080
In many respects, if you look
at this project in detail--

00:46:29.080 --> 00:46:31.840
particularly the
drawings, he draws,

00:46:31.840 --> 00:46:33.610
and his wife draws, beautifully.

00:46:37.910 --> 00:46:47.190
In order to create enough
identity in a 15,000-person,

00:46:47.190 --> 00:46:54.170
place even at this density,
he has to introduce a linear

00:46:54.170 --> 00:47:02.330
system down the middle, full
of large buildings, hotels,

00:47:02.330 --> 00:47:04.340
convention centers.

00:47:04.340 --> 00:47:09.680
No 15,000 part of a city
can support economically

00:47:09.680 --> 00:47:11.570
this kind of program.

00:47:11.570 --> 00:47:16.370
One of the problems that
the new urbanists have

00:47:16.370 --> 00:47:20.060
is that in American
densities, if you were not

00:47:20.060 --> 00:47:24.470
willing to walk more
than seven minutes,

00:47:24.470 --> 00:47:28.340
you can drive to a
7-Eleven and a video store,

00:47:28.340 --> 00:47:31.820
let alone to the
diversity of shopping

00:47:31.820 --> 00:47:34.640
or commercial
opportunities that you have

00:47:34.640 --> 00:47:37.490
if you increase the density.

00:47:37.490 --> 00:47:40.010
Suburbia is fraught
with the problem

00:47:40.010 --> 00:47:43.580
of having too few people.

00:47:43.580 --> 00:47:46.530
You can inflate it
as much as you can.

00:47:46.530 --> 00:47:49.520
The second problem with
this clear preoccupation

00:47:49.520 --> 00:47:55.010
with classicism is that it
doesn't allow for diversity.

00:47:59.220 --> 00:48:03.900
The piece I quoted from
myself, in discussion

00:48:03.900 --> 00:48:08.220
with Leon Krier at one
meeting, argues that argument.

00:48:14.280 --> 00:48:20.160
Let's go on, because I don't
want to run out of time,

00:48:20.160 --> 00:48:21.525
to discussion of memory.

00:48:28.070 --> 00:48:30.910
We know a lot more about
memory than we used to.

00:48:33.680 --> 00:48:41.150
Across the street, there
are bunch of people.

00:48:41.150 --> 00:48:43.070
One of the institutes
is the institute

00:48:43.070 --> 00:48:46.460
for memory, the
Picower Institute.

00:48:49.420 --> 00:48:53.440
What we know about
memory is that it

00:48:53.440 --> 00:48:55.570
operates through
the existence of 10

00:48:55.570 --> 00:48:58.060
to the power of 12 neurons.

00:48:58.060 --> 00:49:01.460
And what is 10 to
the power of 12?

00:49:01.460 --> 00:49:04.480
That's the number of
neurons in the human brain.

00:49:04.480 --> 00:49:15.540
Each neuron is connected to
plus-minus 5,000 other cells.

00:49:15.540 --> 00:49:20.120
So you have a network
of immense power.

00:49:20.120 --> 00:49:23.930
50% of memory is created--

00:49:34.400 --> 00:49:39.710
not memory, I'm
sorry, on perception.

00:49:39.710 --> 00:49:44.840
Vision commands almost one
half of our brain's cortex.

00:49:44.840 --> 00:49:48.140
To make sense of a picture
that you see through your eyes

00:49:48.140 --> 00:49:51.710
takes half the power.

00:49:51.710 --> 00:49:54.260
This requires more
computational power

00:49:54.260 --> 00:50:01.820
than the MIT engineers can
fathom, let alone produce.

00:50:01.820 --> 00:50:06.320
Nancy Kanwisher, a
professor across the street,

00:50:06.320 --> 00:50:08.090
writes the following.

00:50:08.090 --> 00:50:11.060
I'm quoting her because I
don't want to make mistakes.

00:50:15.845 --> 00:50:19.220
"Object recognition
is no trivial task,

00:50:19.220 --> 00:50:23.360
because the visual image doesn't
enter our brains as a developed

00:50:23.360 --> 00:50:25.770
photograph."

00:50:25.770 --> 00:50:28.730
Imagine that most of
architectural expression

00:50:28.730 --> 00:50:35.832
that I'm talking about is
processed by the visual brain.

00:50:35.832 --> 00:50:38.510
"Rather, it is like
a grid of pixels

00:50:38.510 --> 00:50:42.380
on a digital camera, an
array of millions of numbers

00:50:42.380 --> 00:50:46.670
indicating light and color
on our eyes' 10 million

00:50:46.670 --> 00:50:50.920
or so photoreceptors.

00:50:50.920 --> 00:50:53.050
As you walk down
the street, billions

00:50:53.050 --> 00:50:59.140
of bits of visual information
strike your field of view.

00:50:59.140 --> 00:51:03.820
That view refreshes itself
continuously as objects move,

00:51:03.820 --> 00:51:08.080
lighting changes, or you
shift your eyes or your body.

00:51:08.080 --> 00:51:10.090
Still, the briefest
glance is often

00:51:10.090 --> 00:51:14.560
enough to recognize even a
never-before-seen objects.

00:51:14.560 --> 00:51:17.770
In a fraction of a
second, its visual input

00:51:17.770 --> 00:51:21.090
runs from the retina through
increasing the [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:21.090 --> 00:51:25.060
of the visual stream until it
reaches the cognitive regions

00:51:25.060 --> 00:51:25.710
of the brain."

00:51:29.090 --> 00:51:30.490
I'm amazed at this.

00:51:36.290 --> 00:51:41.820
Processing of visual
information is not automatic.

00:51:41.820 --> 00:51:43.070
It is selective.

00:51:43.070 --> 00:51:48.470
What you decide to send to
the higher parts of your brain

00:51:48.470 --> 00:51:55.160
is based on the selection you
make in the image you see.

00:51:55.160 --> 00:51:58.040
Memory is very
difficult to deal with.

00:52:01.370 --> 00:52:05.570
We know it exists
because we have access

00:52:05.570 --> 00:52:07.510
to the cells of the individual.

00:52:07.510 --> 00:52:09.020
But what is collective memory?

00:52:12.160 --> 00:52:15.070
I'm going to go through
a bunch of theses.

00:52:17.990 --> 00:52:22.900
Let's see if I can goes through
those lists of distinctions.

00:52:29.830 --> 00:52:37.000
Here, I'm giving you a
list of five writers who've

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:39.070
tried to distinguish
history and memory.

00:52:42.710 --> 00:52:50.735
Number 1, "When history ends,
memory begins," Aldo Rossi.

00:52:53.680 --> 00:52:57.250
History precedes
memory-- his argument

00:52:57.250 --> 00:53:01.480
is that when a building
changes its function,

00:53:01.480 --> 00:53:05.620
it invokes memory and ends
history, which is nonsense.

00:53:09.790 --> 00:53:12.370
Maurice Halbwachs
says, general history

00:53:12.370 --> 00:53:16.315
only starts when tradition
ends and the social memory

00:53:16.315 --> 00:53:19.210
is folding or breaking up.

00:53:19.210 --> 00:53:22.820
This is the conventional
interpretation.

00:53:22.820 --> 00:53:26.920
Memory, if it is as
Halbwachs argues, the result

00:53:26.920 --> 00:53:29.110
of social interaction.

00:53:29.110 --> 00:53:31.900
Halbwachs is very outspoken.

00:53:31.900 --> 00:53:37.510
He writes a chapter on musical
memory, which is extraordinary.

00:53:37.510 --> 00:53:41.260
He argues that it is impossible
to maintain musical memory

00:53:41.260 --> 00:53:45.010
without being part of a group.

00:53:45.010 --> 00:53:51.100
I am often amazed that a
pianist like Mauricio Pollini

00:53:51.100 --> 00:53:59.680
will walk onto a stage
and play for three hours

00:53:59.680 --> 00:54:03.670
without looking at a note.

00:54:03.670 --> 00:54:07.570
He'll play from Beethoven,
he'll play from Chopin,

00:54:07.570 --> 00:54:10.140
he'll play from--

00:54:10.140 --> 00:54:11.980
well, whoever he plays from.

00:54:15.860 --> 00:54:19.730
We still don't know, because
we can't penetrate the brain

00:54:19.730 --> 00:54:22.530
medically.

00:54:22.530 --> 00:54:25.280
You can do it only if
you operate on tumors,

00:54:25.280 --> 00:54:27.170
but you cannot--

00:54:27.170 --> 00:54:32.690
most of disease is
understood through symptoms

00:54:32.690 --> 00:54:35.600
or through blood measurements.

00:54:35.600 --> 00:54:40.620
You can get neither very
directly from the brain.

00:54:40.620 --> 00:54:44.060
So the brain is the last
part of the human body that

00:54:44.060 --> 00:54:49.100
is subject to
research in medicine,

00:54:49.100 --> 00:54:52.160
and the distance it
has to go particularly

00:54:52.160 --> 00:54:54.350
for the neurodegenerative
diseases--

00:54:54.350 --> 00:55:01.190
Alzheimer's, Parkinson's,
autism, schizophrenia,

00:55:01.190 --> 00:55:04.970
is long, long away,
although they are doing

00:55:04.970 --> 00:55:06.560
good work across the street.

00:55:09.120 --> 00:55:15.800
So these assumptions about
memory are approximations.

00:55:21.390 --> 00:55:26.020
The only person who has a
very strong view on this

00:55:26.020 --> 00:55:29.520
is Pierre Nora the
French philosopher,

00:55:29.520 --> 00:55:33.930
who says, "Memory is life born
by living societies founded

00:55:33.930 --> 00:55:35.490
in its name.

00:55:35.490 --> 00:55:38.550
History, on the other hand,
is the reconstruction,

00:55:38.550 --> 00:55:41.040
always problematic
and incomplete,

00:55:41.040 --> 00:55:43.140
of what is no longer.

00:55:43.140 --> 00:55:46.590
History is perpetually
suspicious of memory,

00:55:46.590 --> 00:55:50.520
and its true mission is to
suppress and destroy it."

00:55:50.520 --> 00:55:56.520
This is very antagonistic
view of history's claim

00:55:56.520 --> 00:56:02.640
to coincide with memory,
time separating the two.

00:56:02.640 --> 00:56:08.100
He argues that
colonization is based

00:56:08.100 --> 00:56:11.520
on destroying the
memory component

00:56:11.520 --> 00:56:15.030
of native civilizations.

00:56:15.030 --> 00:56:20.200
He also says that postmodernism,
with false history,

00:56:20.200 --> 00:56:24.480
fake history, sound
bites, virtual history,

00:56:24.480 --> 00:56:27.550
compounds the problem.

00:56:27.550 --> 00:56:33.330
Let's look at some of this
material a little more

00:56:33.330 --> 00:56:36.380
carefully.

00:56:36.380 --> 00:56:41.170
History has a long association--

00:56:41.170 --> 00:56:45.155
sorry, architecture has a
long association with memory.

00:56:50.600 --> 00:56:55.940
The mnemonic device
for remembering

00:56:55.940 --> 00:57:02.480
is absolutely present in
the earliest histories.

00:57:02.480 --> 00:57:06.020
Memory is quoted in
by Cicero and others

00:57:06.020 --> 00:57:12.500
as occurring when the Greek
Simonedes is at a meeting,

00:57:12.500 --> 00:57:16.280
and leaves the meeting
because he's cold outside.

00:57:16.280 --> 00:57:18.140
While he's outside,
the building's roof

00:57:18.140 --> 00:57:21.530
collapses and kills
everybody in the room.

00:57:21.530 --> 00:57:26.460
He has a capacity of memory,
which reconstructs everybody,

00:57:26.460 --> 00:57:29.690
although the bodies
are disfigured.

00:57:29.690 --> 00:57:32.570
The notion that if
that act of memory

00:57:32.570 --> 00:57:36.470
was an important
phenomenon [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:36.470 --> 00:57:42.110
classical societies
is made evident

00:57:42.110 --> 00:57:53.180
by the role that mnemonics
played in Greek education.

00:57:53.180 --> 00:57:54.650
Young men would walk--

00:57:54.650 --> 00:57:58.160
not women, young men would
walk around the pyramid,

00:57:58.160 --> 00:58:01.490
and they're concentrating
on the [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:01.490 --> 00:58:05.090
the architectural
elements of the system.

00:58:05.090 --> 00:58:07.100
They'd walk round
and round and roun

00:58:07.100 --> 00:58:10.280
until it imprinted their minds.

00:58:10.280 --> 00:58:13.567
They were open to question
about the constructions

00:58:13.567 --> 00:58:14.150
of the orders.

00:58:17.900 --> 00:58:24.335
Young men were taught to
debate using architecture

00:58:24.335 --> 00:58:25.235
as a mnemonic.

00:58:28.050 --> 00:58:29.290
You make an argument.

00:58:29.290 --> 00:58:32.740
You enter into the
foyer of the building.

00:58:32.740 --> 00:58:35.050
You make your argument.

00:58:35.050 --> 00:58:37.600
You turn right into a room.

00:58:37.600 --> 00:58:39.100
That's your sub-argument.

00:58:39.100 --> 00:58:41.200
You return to the main argument.

00:58:41.200 --> 00:58:42.610
You go to the left.

00:58:42.610 --> 00:58:44.980
You make another
second sub-argument.

00:58:44.980 --> 00:58:46.720
You return to the center.

00:58:46.720 --> 00:58:48.250
You go up a staircase.

00:58:48.250 --> 00:58:50.230
You go to the third of the left.

00:58:50.230 --> 00:58:52.360
You return to the main argument.

00:58:52.360 --> 00:58:54.340
You go to the fourth, and so on.

00:58:54.340 --> 00:58:57.310
This is a very classical
form of learning.

00:58:57.310 --> 00:59:04.060
But when memory was not
available through television

00:59:04.060 --> 00:59:07.630
or through radio or through
telephones and so on,

00:59:07.630 --> 00:59:10.870
it was a very
precious commodity.

00:59:10.870 --> 00:59:23.180
And architecture as a space
is an important mnemonic.

00:59:23.180 --> 00:59:26.060
Architecture serves
as a memory system

00:59:26.060 --> 00:59:30.020
for ideas about human
origins, a means for recording

00:59:30.020 --> 00:59:32.960
understanding of order and
relationship in the world,

00:59:32.960 --> 00:59:37.170
and an attempt to grasp the
concept of the internal cosmos,

00:59:37.170 --> 00:59:41.660
which has no fixed dimensions
with neither beginning nor end.

00:59:46.797 --> 00:59:51.350
There are endless references
to the use of mnemonics.

00:59:51.350 --> 00:59:54.800
Frances Yates' book
on memory and culture

00:59:54.800 --> 00:59:57.860
refers to medieval
systems of theater

00:59:57.860 --> 01:00:02.180
writing as
mnemonics-- as devices

01:00:02.180 --> 01:00:05.030
for learning about memory.

01:00:05.030 --> 01:00:09.920
John Ruskin, the 19th
century British art historian

01:00:09.920 --> 01:00:13.730
and philosopher,
writes, "We may remember

01:00:13.730 --> 01:00:16.580
without [INAUDIBLE] memory.

01:00:16.580 --> 01:00:21.600
We may live without memory
and worship without memory.

01:00:21.600 --> 01:00:25.940
But we--" sorry.

01:00:25.940 --> 01:00:28.970
Ruskin wrote a book called
Seven Lamps of Architecture,

01:00:28.970 --> 01:00:31.850
which none of you
know about, I'm sure.

01:00:31.850 --> 01:00:33.470
It's a book.

01:00:33.470 --> 01:00:36.177
Good. how do you know about it?

01:00:36.177 --> 01:00:37.802
AUDIENCE: I took a
class on the history

01:00:37.802 --> 01:00:39.690
of conservation [INAUDIBLE].

01:00:42.420 --> 01:00:46.480
JULIAN BEINART: Seven Lamps
of Architecture-- sacrifice,

01:00:46.480 --> 01:00:50.410
truth, power, beauty,
life, memory, obedience.

01:00:50.410 --> 01:00:55.030
Why would a 19th century
British art historian

01:00:55.030 --> 01:01:00.097
include memory as one of
the lamps of architecture?

01:01:06.590 --> 01:01:09.080
We cannot remember without her.

01:01:11.880 --> 01:01:13.800
These are obsessive arguments.

01:01:17.080 --> 01:01:22.170
But the whole apparatus of
the built world is a mnemonic.

01:01:24.730 --> 01:01:28.190
It's way of us maintaining
our daily life.

01:01:28.190 --> 01:01:30.895
This is Halbwachs' big point.

01:01:30.895 --> 01:01:33.730
I'll come to it in one minute.

01:01:33.730 --> 01:01:38.230
I'm trying to go through the
others as quickly as I can.

01:01:38.230 --> 01:01:47.470
The arguments about-- in
Jacques [INAUDIBLE] book about--

01:01:47.470 --> 01:01:56.490
and in Yale professor
Kirsten Harris'

01:01:56.490 --> 01:02:03.930
writing about the
phenomenon of paradise.

01:02:03.930 --> 01:02:10.890
Paradise Lost is explicit
in its mission to us

01:02:10.890 --> 01:02:15.910
that we have been trying
to recreate paradise.

01:02:15.910 --> 01:02:22.050
[INAUDIBLE] paradise
refers to that.

01:02:22.050 --> 01:02:24.660
[INAUDIBLE] philosophers
have written

01:02:24.660 --> 01:02:26.760
about the loss of paradise.

01:02:26.760 --> 01:02:32.910
Paradise Lost Who wrote the
epic poem Paradise Lost?

01:02:32.910 --> 01:02:35.580
Milton, Yeah.

01:02:35.580 --> 01:02:39.900
I was confusing
with somebody else.

01:02:39.900 --> 01:02:46.200
Harris also argues that we are
the only animal species that

01:02:46.200 --> 01:02:49.170
knows that we're going to die.

01:02:49.170 --> 01:03:00.900
Therefore, our capacity
to be beholden to time

01:03:00.900 --> 01:03:06.960
is greater, this phenomenon
of the building of ruins.

01:03:09.570 --> 01:03:11.760
The single appearance
of artificial--

01:03:11.760 --> 01:03:14.340
how do you explain the
building of artificial ruins

01:03:14.340 --> 01:03:20.880
in the 18th century, given
my argument about memory?

01:03:20.880 --> 01:03:23.640
What is a sophisticated society?

01:03:23.640 --> 01:03:27.390
What is the wealthy and
the sophisticated society

01:03:27.390 --> 01:03:30.285
in [INAUDIBLE] building
ruins on the property?

01:03:38.640 --> 01:03:42.525
We go to Louis Kahn, whom I
quote in my writing on memory.

01:03:46.390 --> 01:03:53.890
In the Hurva synagogue, which
was number 3, which is probably

01:03:53.890 --> 01:03:59.770
Louis Kahn's half
dozen best creations,

01:03:59.770 --> 01:04:03.520
although it wasn't
built, he was asked

01:04:03.520 --> 01:04:07.840
to replace the traditional
Jewish synagogue

01:04:07.840 --> 01:04:10.540
in the old city of Jerusalem.

01:04:10.540 --> 01:04:15.220
He refused the rabbi's
implication and said,

01:04:15.220 --> 01:04:17.330
I'm going to build it
on the site next to it.

01:04:17.330 --> 01:04:19.570
I'm going to maintain the ruins.

01:04:19.570 --> 01:04:23.770
Why did he argue for
maintaining the ruins?

01:04:23.770 --> 01:04:27.460
First rule, Kahn says
ruins maintain memory.

01:04:27.460 --> 01:04:31.240
What is not built
is not really lost.

01:04:31.240 --> 01:04:35.080
Second, a ruin free
of the obligation

01:04:35.080 --> 01:04:38.120
to perform active
functions any longer

01:04:38.120 --> 01:04:42.520
is able to fully express
its spirit or formations,

01:04:42.520 --> 01:04:47.320
often more so than
whole buildings.

01:04:47.320 --> 01:04:49.270
A third aspect of
Kahn's thought is

01:04:49.270 --> 01:04:52.030
his linking of ruins
with the idea of silence.

01:04:55.640 --> 01:05:02.180
And then the fourth, his concept
of the fact that contemporary

01:05:02.180 --> 01:05:07.450
built forms could be given
metaphoric implications

01:05:07.450 --> 01:05:08.062
of ruins.

01:05:14.330 --> 01:05:16.460
The creation of a
perfect paradise

01:05:16.460 --> 01:05:18.980
lies at the center
of architecture.

01:05:21.560 --> 01:05:23.615
Paradise on Earth
is a kind of waiting

01:05:23.615 --> 01:05:29.330
room-- an anticipatory
suburb of kingdom come.

01:05:29.330 --> 01:05:35.270
Maurice Halbwachs
remarks that [INAUDIBLE]

01:05:35.270 --> 01:05:37.580
is first and foremost
due to the fact

01:05:37.580 --> 01:05:40.520
that physical objects
of our daily contact

01:05:40.520 --> 01:05:43.670
change little or not
at all, providing us

01:05:43.670 --> 01:05:46.190
with an image of
permanence and stability.

01:05:50.060 --> 01:05:57.200
If I had to find my mirror
to shave in the morning,

01:05:57.200 --> 01:06:00.260
in a different place
every day, I'd go mad.

01:06:00.260 --> 01:06:03.140
I wouldn't shave.

01:06:03.140 --> 01:06:06.200
If Memorial Drive changed
its function overnight,

01:06:06.200 --> 01:06:10.550
and I had to find a new road
to come to MIT every morning,

01:06:10.550 --> 01:06:12.890
I'd go mad.

01:06:12.890 --> 01:06:17.420
Guy de Maupassant
tells a horrible story

01:06:17.420 --> 01:06:21.620
of a mother and daughter
who come to Paris

01:06:21.620 --> 01:06:23.870
during the plague epidemic.

01:06:23.870 --> 01:06:26.420
The mother doesn't know that
the daughter has plague.

01:06:26.420 --> 01:06:32.360
She hasn't-- they check into a
hotel where they reserved room.

01:06:32.360 --> 01:06:34.700
The manager of the
hotel recognizes

01:06:34.700 --> 01:06:36.770
the plague in the daughter.

01:06:36.770 --> 01:06:39.410
The mother and
daughter check in,

01:06:39.410 --> 01:06:44.000
go out to see doctors
for the rest of the day.

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:46.190
The manager of the
hotel has their room

01:06:46.190 --> 01:06:49.490
changed while they're gone--

01:06:49.490 --> 01:06:50.870
redecorated.

01:06:50.870 --> 01:06:54.200
Their belongings are dispatched.

01:06:54.200 --> 01:06:57.440
They return that night,
and the manager tells them

01:06:57.440 --> 01:06:59.030
that they made a mistake.

01:06:59.030 --> 01:07:00.800
They didn't check
into the hotel.

01:07:03.700 --> 01:07:07.360
Guy de Maupassant
writes the story

01:07:07.360 --> 01:07:12.500
to intrigue us about the need
for permanence [INAUDIBLE]

01:07:12.500 --> 01:07:17.410
about the everyday fact of
checking into a hotel providing

01:07:17.410 --> 01:07:22.330
us with reasonable
expectations or nourishment.

01:07:22.330 --> 01:07:25.210
Halbwachs is very full of this.

01:07:28.890 --> 01:07:30.770
I'll just quote
him in one place.

01:07:38.170 --> 01:07:41.230
"Thus every collective
memory unfolds

01:07:41.230 --> 01:07:43.510
within the spatial framework.

01:07:43.510 --> 01:07:46.300
Space is a reality that endures.

01:07:46.300 --> 01:07:49.210
Since our impressions
rush by one after another

01:07:49.210 --> 01:07:51.610
and leave nothing
behind in the mind,

01:07:51.610 --> 01:07:55.090
we can understand how
we recapture the past,

01:07:55.090 --> 01:07:58.750
but only by understanding
how it is in effect preserved

01:07:58.750 --> 01:08:01.030
by our physical surrounding.

01:08:01.030 --> 01:08:04.930
It is to space, the space
we occupy, traverse,

01:08:04.930 --> 01:08:08.620
have continual access
to, or can at any time

01:08:08.620 --> 01:08:11.440
reconstruct in
thought or imagination

01:08:11.440 --> 01:08:13.540
that we must turn our attention.

01:08:13.540 --> 01:08:16.840
Our thought must focus on
it if this or that category

01:08:16.840 --> 01:08:19.390
of remembrance is to reappear."

01:08:22.279 --> 01:08:26.310
OK, running out
of time as always.

