01:09:30.279 --> 01:09:35.350
We'll now look at one of the
categories of transference

01:09:35.350 --> 01:09:41.410
of tectonic forms literally
to a new building.

01:09:41.410 --> 01:09:45.370
James Ingo Freed writes
about the Holocaust museum.

01:09:45.370 --> 01:09:49.540
"I prefer memory to history
because I prefer the authentic

01:09:49.540 --> 01:09:51.729
to the reconstructed."

01:09:51.729 --> 01:09:53.830
History is reconstructed.

01:09:53.830 --> 01:09:56.650
Critics of history
are always assuming

01:09:56.650 --> 01:09:59.020
that it's reconstructed.

01:09:59.020 --> 01:10:02.860
That it's based upon
somebody else's measurements

01:10:02.860 --> 01:10:06.970
and thought, not the
intuitive impressions that you

01:10:06.970 --> 01:10:10.150
create in your own brain.

01:10:10.150 --> 01:10:15.200
Althouth, as Halbwachs points
out, relying on society.

01:10:15.200 --> 01:10:20.080
"History erases detail
at a painful cost.

01:10:20.080 --> 01:10:23.940
It gains consistency through
abstraction and [INAUDIBLE]

01:10:23.940 --> 01:10:26.740
the loss of the
richness of life.

01:10:26.740 --> 01:10:29.660
As a physical artifact
of a given time,

01:10:29.660 --> 01:10:32.160
place, and culture,
architectures

01:10:32.160 --> 01:10:36.310
an undistorted, unchanged
thread of memory woven

01:10:36.310 --> 01:10:38.005
into the tapestry of history."

01:10:42.110 --> 01:10:45.600
What he says he's trying to do--

01:10:45.600 --> 01:10:47.135
and we'll see in the images.

01:10:49.970 --> 01:10:53.750
"I discovered that the only
way for me into the Holocaust

01:10:53.750 --> 01:10:56.900
was through both the
tectonics of the Holocaust

01:10:56.900 --> 01:11:00.590
and an invented
tectonics of my own.

01:11:00.590 --> 01:11:02.780
There was an architecture
of the Holocaust

01:11:02.780 --> 01:11:06.074
with its own tectonics
that surround the surface."

01:11:08.846 --> 01:11:19.060
What he's saying
is that the source

01:11:19.060 --> 01:11:25.840
of what he wishes to
memorialize has a tectonic form.

01:11:25.840 --> 01:11:28.900
He can abstract some
of those tectonics

01:11:28.900 --> 01:11:31.180
and reproduce them in
the current version

01:11:31.180 --> 01:11:32.470
of the building.

01:11:32.470 --> 01:11:34.000
What are those forms?

01:11:34.000 --> 01:11:42.110
Steel, bricks, the use
of space, the clustering

01:11:42.110 --> 01:11:46.145
of the sequence in which
you go through the museum.

01:11:46.145 --> 01:11:50.510
You know that you go
up before you go down.

01:11:50.510 --> 01:11:56.180
Certain artifacts, such as the
little town which was destroyed

01:11:56.180 --> 01:12:02.670
and all the images plastered
on the ceiling, little devices

01:12:02.670 --> 01:12:04.100
which--

01:12:04.100 --> 01:12:06.920
the elevated
passageways which have

01:12:06.920 --> 01:12:10.940
diagonal structural
reinforcement.

01:12:10.940 --> 01:12:14.840
All of these are
tectonic items which

01:12:14.840 --> 01:12:21.410
are meant to meld the
present and the past,

01:12:21.410 --> 01:12:25.700
meant to inflict themselves
on your memory in a way

01:12:25.700 --> 01:12:29.380
that you are [INAUDIBLE]
with what you're

01:12:29.380 --> 01:12:31.145
seeing as an actual event.

01:12:36.040 --> 01:12:41.590
It's very difficult to know
about when this is crap

01:12:41.590 --> 01:12:45.861
or whether this is
fundamentally powerful stuff.

01:12:45.861 --> 01:12:50.620
We are in an age where
distortions are so absolute

01:12:50.620 --> 01:12:56.890
and borrowing is so absolute
through virtual media that

01:12:56.890 --> 01:13:01.360
[INAUDIBLE] is a
genuine article--

01:13:01.360 --> 01:13:09.050
a genuine borrowing is
difficult to evaluate.

01:13:09.050 --> 01:13:15.860
But I've experienced
the museum a couple

01:13:15.860 --> 01:13:23.060
of times partly as an architect,
partly as just as a citizen.

01:13:25.880 --> 01:13:27.950
The remarkable
thing is that you go

01:13:27.950 --> 01:13:35.240
through the disposition of
evidence, very clinically,

01:13:35.240 --> 01:13:38.840
almost historically
accurate evidence.

01:13:38.840 --> 01:13:41.630
The dates of every
single item are.

01:13:41.630 --> 01:13:48.920
Included the mechanical railroad
car that took Jews to Auschwitz

01:13:48.920 --> 01:13:54.890
is actually there, or
when America turned down

01:13:54.890 --> 01:14:00.870
the boat of immigrants,
that's there.

01:14:00.870 --> 01:14:06.050
Then you go down and you leave
the building through a room.

01:14:06.050 --> 01:14:10.790
And the room is just
based on the voices

01:14:10.790 --> 01:14:14.330
of people who were
in Auschwitz talking

01:14:14.330 --> 01:14:20.880
about things like,
my mother said to me,

01:14:20.880 --> 01:14:22.610
don't worry about the food.

01:14:22.610 --> 01:14:24.020
You eat the food.

01:14:24.020 --> 01:14:26.270
I have had enough already.

01:14:26.270 --> 01:14:28.970
I knew my mother they
had nothing to eat,

01:14:28.970 --> 01:14:32.060
but she was wanting
me to survive.

01:14:32.060 --> 01:14:37.190
The poignancy of that
material touches your memory.

01:14:37.190 --> 01:14:40.670
It evokes your own
experience with your mother

01:14:40.670 --> 01:14:44.070
in Freudian terms.

01:14:44.070 --> 01:14:49.640
So in the piece of
writing I've given to you,

01:14:49.640 --> 01:14:54.110
Stan Anderson writes a
piece at a conference which

01:14:54.110 --> 01:14:59.480
I ran in 1994 about memory.

01:14:59.480 --> 01:15:06.095
And Freed and the
French philosopher

01:15:06.095 --> 01:15:10.430
whom I quoted
about memory seemed

01:15:10.430 --> 01:15:17.480
to indicate that we have this
bifocal impression, knowledge

01:15:17.480 --> 01:15:19.130
of the past--

01:15:19.130 --> 01:15:23.990
history which is categorical
and empirical and selected

01:15:23.990 --> 01:15:35.150
by other people, an apparently
objective rendition of my past,

01:15:35.150 --> 01:15:40.130
and my own rendition of
my past, which is lively,

01:15:40.130 --> 01:15:45.830
irregular, full of obstacles,
full of juxtapositions.

01:15:45.830 --> 01:15:50.540
Like Freud says, I
can't externalize what

01:15:50.540 --> 01:15:54.770
I remember visually very well.

01:15:54.770 --> 01:15:59.810
I could draw my mother next to
my daughter and my grandmother

01:15:59.810 --> 01:16:03.260
and the woman I
see in my dreams,

01:16:03.260 --> 01:16:05.270
but I can't put them
all together as I

01:16:05.270 --> 01:16:07.820
can in my psychic experience.

01:16:10.990 --> 01:16:22.630
There's a politics of memory,
the Jews maintaining memory

01:16:22.630 --> 01:16:26.860
through the book, through
the remembrance of Jerusalem

01:16:26.860 --> 01:16:31.300
on an annual ritual,
and so on and so on.

01:16:31.300 --> 01:16:36.490
I gave you this piece
from The Boston Globe,

01:16:36.490 --> 01:16:40.360
which is interesting, because
it's a selective memory

01:16:40.360 --> 01:16:41.040
situation.

01:16:41.040 --> 01:16:45.190
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:16:45.190 --> 01:16:46.610
JULIAN BEINART: Oh, yeah.

01:16:46.610 --> 01:16:51.370
Sorry, I'll give
you the references.

01:16:51.370 --> 01:16:55.180
Mass xeroxing often
cuts out the top.

01:16:55.180 --> 01:16:59.620
It's a critique of Rossi's
book written by, I think,

01:16:59.620 --> 01:17:05.350
Francesco [INAUDIBLE] And
I'll give you the reference.

01:17:10.270 --> 01:17:26.970
At this time of these textile
mills in Lowell, one of us

01:17:26.970 --> 01:17:28.620
here thought how
wonderful it would

01:17:28.620 --> 01:17:33.600
be if we could put the new
University of Massachusetts

01:17:33.600 --> 01:17:34.650
branch.

01:17:34.650 --> 01:17:35.310
Where's Lowell?

01:17:35.310 --> 01:17:37.140
Lowell's in
Massachusetts, isn't it?

01:17:37.140 --> 01:17:38.466
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:17:38.466 --> 01:17:41.280
JULIAN BEINART: Into
these old buildings.

01:17:41.280 --> 01:17:44.310
And we were all doing
sketches in studios

01:17:44.310 --> 01:17:49.660
showing how wonderful
it would be to do this.

01:17:49.660 --> 01:17:52.180
Here's a man who says
those memories were awful.

01:17:56.170 --> 01:18:02.360
What are you memorizing things
of the past that we find awful?

01:18:02.360 --> 01:18:07.090
It's a memory, again,
selectively experienced.

01:18:07.090 --> 01:18:14.510
How you, as a professional,
condition your own memory with

01:18:14.510 --> 01:18:19.060
the memory [INAUDIBLE] people,
presumably such a lively

01:18:19.060 --> 01:18:23.830
function that the only
thing you can do is--

01:18:26.690 --> 01:18:30.250
in this memory world,
there's some strange things.

01:18:30.250 --> 01:18:40.600
There's an MCP thesis done in
which the student was a trained

01:18:40.600 --> 01:18:42.220
philosopher--

01:18:42.220 --> 01:18:46.150
a phenomenologist.

01:18:46.150 --> 01:18:51.340
And he wrote about
his parents' apartment

01:18:51.340 --> 01:18:58.110
in New York and growing
up, and his reactions when

01:18:58.110 --> 01:19:01.200
they changed the room when
he left to go to college

01:19:01.200 --> 01:19:04.020
and rented the room.

01:19:04.020 --> 01:19:07.635
His whole thesis was
based upon his dreams.

01:19:10.230 --> 01:19:11.720
Fact is, it was a lie.

01:19:11.720 --> 01:19:13.250
He never had those dreams.

01:19:13.250 --> 01:19:16.880
He reinvented the
dreams for his thesis.

01:19:16.880 --> 01:19:19.670
So it was a complex
mixture of data.

01:19:19.670 --> 01:19:26.690
He should have been failed,
but nobody knew the reality

01:19:26.690 --> 01:19:29.090
until he told us afterwards.

01:19:29.090 --> 01:19:32.540
But it was such a
brilliant set of occasions,

01:19:32.540 --> 01:19:38.270
of being two foot tall and
seeing the refrigerator

01:19:38.270 --> 01:19:39.560
and what it meant.

01:19:39.560 --> 01:19:43.040
Seeing the large bed that his
mother and father slept in,

01:19:43.040 --> 01:19:46.130
and wondering why they
needed such a large bed,

01:19:46.130 --> 01:19:52.650
and dreaming of
interpolations of that

01:19:52.650 --> 01:19:57.350
as remembered by an adult
and what that would mean

01:19:57.350 --> 01:20:00.645
for architecture understanding.

01:20:00.645 --> 01:20:01.145
Anyway.

01:20:14.770 --> 01:20:17.710
I won't be able
to deal with some

01:20:17.710 --> 01:20:22.360
of the examples
from Washington as

01:20:22.360 --> 01:20:26.680
well as I would showing
the history of monuments

01:20:26.680 --> 01:20:27.550
in Washington.

01:20:30.700 --> 01:20:36.250
The amazing thing is that
none of the classical features

01:20:36.250 --> 01:20:44.650
of monuments were maintained
since the Vietnam Memorial.

01:20:44.650 --> 01:20:46.030
A couple of things
have happened.

01:20:46.030 --> 01:20:49.215
Number one, the World
War II Memorial,

01:20:49.215 --> 01:20:55.620
there's a neoclassical
construction--

01:20:55.620 --> 01:20:59.560
a Leon Krier construction
with absolutely no

01:20:59.560 --> 01:21:03.940
merit at all, other than
in the merit of nostalgia.

01:21:07.060 --> 01:21:12.420
Maya Lin's Vietnam Memorial
is an extraordinary adventure.

01:21:12.420 --> 01:21:16.320
It takes the idea of
connecting a monument

01:21:16.320 --> 01:21:18.960
to individual
experience by putting

01:21:18.960 --> 01:21:21.780
the names of the people.

01:21:21.780 --> 01:21:26.790
Your grandson will be able to
go to that name in 25 years time

01:21:26.790 --> 01:21:29.980
or 100 years time.

01:21:29.980 --> 01:21:33.430
Ross Perot's
objection and the need

01:21:33.430 --> 01:21:39.040
to add a soldier a
figure at the entrance

01:21:39.040 --> 01:21:44.530
is a stupid attempt to add
nostalgia to the abstraction.

01:21:44.530 --> 01:21:49.160
The power of monuments often
lies in its abstraction,

01:21:49.160 --> 01:21:52.270
in its being of
cleansed of irrelevance.

01:21:52.270 --> 01:21:56.080
The obelisk of Washington,
I will show you

01:21:56.080 --> 01:22:01.000
a slide that in the 19th
century, people in Washington--

01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:07.350
certain people wanted to
garnish the obelisk memorial

01:22:07.350 --> 01:22:11.580
with evidence of the
inner decoration.

01:22:15.450 --> 01:22:17.790
What has happened
in recent times

01:22:17.790 --> 01:22:25.380
is that we've lost the capacity,
it seems in architecture,

01:22:25.380 --> 01:22:30.770
to memorialize through objects,
through forms themselves.

01:22:30.770 --> 01:22:34.112
AUDIENCE: Is that because
we're lacking the capacity

01:22:34.112 --> 01:22:36.022
to see beyond the evidence?

01:22:36.022 --> 01:22:37.230
JULIAN BEINART: I don't know.

01:22:37.230 --> 01:22:38.670
I wish I could answer that.

01:22:44.210 --> 01:22:54.530
The version of the Roosevelt
Memorial, which is a garden,

01:22:54.530 --> 01:22:59.280
dispenses with the
need of architecture.

01:22:59.280 --> 01:23:03.570
The three versions of
the Roosevelt Memorial,

01:23:03.570 --> 01:23:08.400
which I will have shown you,
are large slabs of stone.

01:23:08.400 --> 01:23:12.490
From stone to garden is
one of the ways in which

01:23:12.490 --> 01:23:17.280
American culture dispenses
with things it can't deal with,

01:23:17.280 --> 01:23:20.740
or has inadequate solutions for.

01:23:20.740 --> 01:23:23.460
Nature's always
there to accommodate.

01:23:26.490 --> 01:23:29.550
If you lose in
man-made construction,

01:23:29.550 --> 01:23:31.050
nature is always there.

01:23:34.140 --> 01:23:38.700
That's why I have my doubts
about the constant evocation

01:23:38.700 --> 01:23:39.990
of nature.

01:23:39.990 --> 01:23:45.420
Nature's too friendly a partner
when examined superficially.

01:23:45.420 --> 01:23:51.030
We'll look at some of
these images on Thursday

01:23:51.030 --> 01:23:53.490
and see if we can remember
the arguments we made.

01:24:05.240 --> 01:24:08.900
The left diagram is
from Rossi's book.

01:24:08.900 --> 01:24:11.420
In fact, both diagrams
are from Rossi's book.

01:24:14.060 --> 01:24:20.180
You will recall, Rossi
argues a number of themes--

01:24:20.180 --> 01:24:23.780
one about the relationship
between the city

01:24:23.780 --> 01:24:28.880
of the mind and the built city;
number two, between permanences

01:24:28.880 --> 01:24:35.700
and temporary parts
of cities; thirdly,

01:24:35.700 --> 01:24:39.860
be the relationship between
institutions and forms,

01:24:39.860 --> 01:24:41.730
and so on and so on.

01:24:41.730 --> 01:24:48.140
Essentially, his argument is
that the ideas and examples

01:24:48.140 --> 01:24:53.420
fossilized in the city which
are worth excavating and using

01:24:53.420 --> 01:24:58.400
is a template for future growth.

01:24:58.400 --> 01:25:02.060
The Palazzo [INAUDIBLE]
on the left,

01:25:02.060 --> 01:25:08.510
destroyed by a hurricane in
1956 and rebuilt with different

01:25:08.510 --> 01:25:12.830
uses, but maintaining
its place in the city.

01:25:12.830 --> 01:25:16.460
The example on the right
is Carlo Fontana's attempt

01:25:16.460 --> 01:25:21.350
to make the Colosseum into
a church, the argument,

01:25:21.350 --> 01:25:23.840
again, that the
framework of the form

01:25:23.840 --> 01:25:28.970
is significant in realizing
an institutional change

01:25:28.970 --> 01:25:32.150
from the killing of
Christians to the celebrating

01:25:32.150 --> 01:25:35.030
of the life of Jesus.

01:25:35.030 --> 01:25:37.760
It doesn't seem to matter.

01:25:37.760 --> 01:25:39.080
Next.

01:25:39.080 --> 01:25:40.130
OK.

01:25:40.130 --> 01:25:42.620
This is [INAUDIBLE] in France.

01:25:42.620 --> 01:25:46.880
The influence of the permanence
of the surrounding wall

01:25:46.880 --> 01:25:52.490
in Lucca, the Roman
Forum, as an antecedent

01:25:52.490 --> 01:25:55.530
to the most important
public place in the city.

01:25:55.530 --> 01:25:56.030
Next.

01:26:01.820 --> 01:26:06.160
Spalato in the
former Yugoslavia.

01:26:10.840 --> 01:26:13.840
An example of the slow--

01:26:13.840 --> 01:26:24.970
this is Hadrian's palace, which
is slowly and over time taken

01:26:24.970 --> 01:26:27.880
up by other people and invaded.

01:26:27.880 --> 01:26:31.810
And the invasion and the
subsequent disjunction

01:26:31.810 --> 01:26:36.310
between what is there in the
past and what is now built

01:26:36.310 --> 01:26:40.270
is of interest to Rossi.

01:26:40.270 --> 01:26:44.350
This slide on the right is
from the Architettura Razionale

01:26:44.350 --> 01:26:46.150
exhibition in Rome.

01:26:46.150 --> 01:26:47.785
I don't know the date.

01:26:47.785 --> 01:26:50.860
It's an important image.

01:26:50.860 --> 01:26:55.450
It's public housing
or social housing

01:26:55.450 --> 01:26:59.620
on Karl-Marx-Allee in at
that time East Berlin.

01:26:59.620 --> 01:27:03.620
The argument is that
locus is significant,

01:27:03.620 --> 01:27:07.810
even if the
architectural form isn't.

01:27:07.810 --> 01:27:11.800
As the argument would go,
this is the equivalent

01:27:11.800 --> 01:27:18.100
of putting social housing
on Fifth Avenue in New York.

01:27:18.100 --> 01:27:24.970
By manifesting locus, or
the importance of location,

01:27:24.970 --> 01:27:28.390
you send important
messages not only

01:27:28.390 --> 01:27:35.005
about the form of the city, but
the meaning of its retention.

01:27:35.005 --> 01:27:35.505
Next.

01:27:38.990 --> 01:27:46.250
The project in Gallaratesse,
a housing project in Milano,

01:27:46.250 --> 01:27:51.710
designed by Aymonino
and Aldo Rossi

01:27:51.710 --> 01:27:59.600
has this extraordinary
empty set of spaces

01:27:59.600 --> 01:28:03.440
underneath the
housing on the right.

01:28:03.440 --> 01:28:10.050
The idea is that people
who are migrating

01:28:10.050 --> 01:28:16.260
to live in this housing in the
north used to live above shops.

01:28:16.260 --> 01:28:19.990
This is a theme which, if
you're ever interested,

01:28:19.990 --> 01:28:23.820
you should look at
[INAUDIBLE] and look

01:28:23.820 --> 01:28:28.560
at Giancarlo De Carlo's project
in Matera, which I showed you

01:28:28.560 --> 01:28:32.310
very briefly, where he
makes a point of maintaining

01:28:32.310 --> 01:28:35.580
the shopping
underneath the housing.

01:28:35.580 --> 01:28:39.960
Here, Rossi does an
abstraction of it.

01:28:39.960 --> 01:28:43.890
There is no need for
shopping in this project.

01:28:43.890 --> 01:28:48.090
So he relies on people's
memory, and gives them

01:28:48.090 --> 01:28:55.950
enough clues apparently to
situate virtual shopping

01:28:55.950 --> 01:28:58.650
in this space, which is--

01:28:58.650 --> 01:29:05.400
it's a crazy idea, but
he does crazy things.

01:29:05.400 --> 01:29:09.330
It's also in line with
his own architecture,

01:29:09.330 --> 01:29:17.910
which has reduced alphabet
of forms as the basis

01:29:17.910 --> 01:29:20.335
for making new things.

01:29:20.335 --> 01:29:20.835
Next.

01:29:24.560 --> 01:29:27.730
I was going to show
you two projects

01:29:27.730 --> 01:29:33.220
in San Francisco, which have
relied on the idea of locus

01:29:33.220 --> 01:29:35.560
in redeveloping.

01:29:35.560 --> 01:29:44.320
On the left is the plan of the
Berkeley cooperative society,

01:29:44.320 --> 01:29:49.360
which owns the land on the right
of the [INAUDIBLE] Building,

01:29:49.360 --> 01:29:54.280
and it wishes to
engage in building

01:29:54.280 --> 01:29:58.570
public housing on the property.

01:29:58.570 --> 01:30:05.020
The architects, Marvin
Buchanan and Donlyn Lyndon,

01:30:05.020 --> 01:30:07.480
argue that replacing
all the buildings

01:30:07.480 --> 01:30:12.070
would delete the important
elements of the existing

01:30:12.070 --> 01:30:13.730
context.

01:30:13.730 --> 01:30:18.100
The second thing is that, unlike
public housing where people

01:30:18.100 --> 01:30:21.910
are moved from where they
are to somewhere else,

01:30:21.910 --> 01:30:28.030
this maintains the
possibility of maintaining

01:30:28.030 --> 01:30:35.680
the place of where these people
are in relation to the Berkeley

01:30:35.680 --> 01:30:37.955
campus just down the road.

01:30:37.955 --> 01:30:38.455
Next.

01:30:42.520 --> 01:30:48.730
By choosing to build
public housing in such

01:30:48.730 --> 01:30:55.720
a contorted site, it
demands the introduction

01:30:55.720 --> 01:31:02.990
of more diverse forms
of housing than normal.

01:31:02.990 --> 01:31:08.200
This slide on the left shows
the attempt to maintain a tree

01:31:08.200 --> 01:31:10.270
and build around it.

01:31:10.270 --> 01:31:13.180
On the right is the
community celebration

01:31:13.180 --> 01:31:16.480
for the opening of the housing.

01:31:16.480 --> 01:31:20.740
The point here is
that the locus is

01:31:20.740 --> 01:31:24.910
the relationship in
space between a place

01:31:24.910 --> 01:31:26.950
and its surroundings.

01:31:26.950 --> 01:31:33.490
Building on that, or creating
a new version of that idea,

01:31:33.490 --> 01:31:37.085
is essentially what
this place has done.

01:31:37.085 --> 01:31:37.585
Next.

01:31:41.040 --> 01:31:45.090
This is a project on
the edge of Chinatown

01:31:45.090 --> 01:31:50.700
in San Francisco at the corner
of Stockton and Sacramento

01:31:50.700 --> 01:31:51.930
Street.

01:31:51.930 --> 01:31:55.830
It's a very steeply
sloping site, which

01:31:55.830 --> 01:31:58.770
went through three versions.

01:31:58.770 --> 01:32:02.850
The first version had
told two tall towers.

01:32:02.850 --> 01:32:07.620
And the basement
and the elevation

01:32:07.620 --> 01:32:11.790
on Stockton Street, which is the
main street through Chinatown,

01:32:11.790 --> 01:32:15.090
was given over to
parking and to shops.

01:32:18.460 --> 01:32:21.030
This was during
Richard Nixon's time.

01:32:21.030 --> 01:32:26.040
Richard Nixon needed votes
in California, rather than

01:32:26.040 --> 01:32:29.670
San Francisco, rather badly,
and the federal government

01:32:29.670 --> 01:32:33.850
allowed this project to
go through two stages.

01:32:33.850 --> 01:32:37.740
So helped by the local
community churches,

01:32:37.740 --> 01:32:42.870
the project ultimately
resulted in two lower towers,

01:32:42.870 --> 01:32:47.070
both for the Chinese
social housing,

01:32:47.070 --> 01:32:50.220
and the ground floor
turned over to a community

01:32:50.220 --> 01:32:53.940
center and a daycare
center, and the parking

01:32:53.940 --> 01:32:57.840
limited to Chinese groups.

01:32:57.840 --> 01:33:02.280
Just further up the
hill is Nob Hill,

01:33:02.280 --> 01:33:06.180
which is some of the most
expensive housing in San

01:33:06.180 --> 01:33:07.080
Francisco.

01:33:09.770 --> 01:33:17.390
This is the opening
of the housing.

01:33:17.390 --> 01:33:20.570
Halfway up the hill,
the project has

01:33:20.570 --> 01:33:25.620
a plane, which is only a
horizontal plane available.

01:33:25.620 --> 01:33:29.660
And that is made
into a public space

01:33:29.660 --> 01:33:30.945
at the center of the housing.

01:33:30.945 --> 01:33:31.445
Next.

01:33:34.470 --> 01:33:38.850
You can see the slope looking
downwards and the diagram

01:33:38.850 --> 01:33:40.950
on the right.

01:33:40.950 --> 01:33:45.900
This is all published in
Society & Space for those of you

01:33:45.900 --> 01:33:50.080
interested in researching
this any further.

01:33:50.080 --> 01:33:50.580
Next.

01:33:56.650 --> 01:34:06.350
Another contemporary version
of the issue of locus

01:34:06.350 --> 01:34:13.640
is through the highly publicized
invention of the marketplace.

01:34:13.640 --> 01:34:17.120
Michael Sorkin is rather
nasty about most things,

01:34:17.120 --> 01:34:22.220
calls it a happy
festival place, implying

01:34:22.220 --> 01:34:26.840
that you have to be happy
to enjoy the world of this

01:34:26.840 --> 01:34:38.750
[INAUDIBLE] In both projects,
which maintain the site,

01:34:38.750 --> 01:34:44.930
the notion of the program
is maintained as well.

01:34:44.930 --> 01:34:49.940
Food becomes the
basis of the new site.

01:34:49.940 --> 01:34:58.010
And although the food is
highly selective and priced

01:34:58.010 --> 01:35:03.140
to a market of a
singular kind, there's

01:35:03.140 --> 01:35:08.240
is not much diversity
of population or places

01:35:08.240 --> 01:35:11.145
in this environment.

01:35:11.145 --> 01:35:11.645
Next.

01:35:15.400 --> 01:35:17.740
This is South
Street Seaport done

01:35:17.740 --> 01:35:21.250
by the same
architects as Faneuil

01:35:21.250 --> 01:35:23.740
[INAUDIBLE] Marketplace.

01:35:23.740 --> 01:35:29.950
Here again, it's building
on the locus, if you want,

01:35:29.950 --> 01:35:34.370
of the existing fish market.

01:35:34.370 --> 01:35:34.870
Next.

01:35:38.480 --> 01:35:41.510
A third version of
this comparatively

01:35:41.510 --> 01:35:42.950
is Pike Place in Seattle.

01:35:45.620 --> 01:35:50.990
Pike Place in Seattle has been
memorialized by the painter

01:35:50.990 --> 01:35:57.290
Mark Tobey on the right and the
existing market on the left.

01:35:57.290 --> 01:36:01.940
This was a market where
farmers would bring produce

01:36:01.940 --> 01:36:05.240
into the town, and
people would buy directly

01:36:05.240 --> 01:36:07.430
from the market here.

01:36:07.430 --> 01:36:12.470
There would be no middleman,
no second order clientele.

01:36:12.470 --> 01:36:18.660
In Faneuil Marketplace,
we have British tea sold,

01:36:18.660 --> 01:36:23.870
which is a commodity so removed
from any direct relationship

01:36:23.870 --> 01:36:26.630
between consumer and producer.

01:36:26.630 --> 01:36:34.395
Here, the tradition is
established in these images.

01:36:34.395 --> 01:36:34.895
Next.

01:36:38.610 --> 01:36:44.460
Threatened by urban renewal,
the project on the left

01:36:44.460 --> 01:36:49.290
determines to remove the
vestiges of the market

01:36:49.290 --> 01:36:50.820
altogether.

01:36:50.820 --> 01:36:56.040
And public opposition, organized
by some of the university

01:36:56.040 --> 01:37:05.280
faculty, maintain the idea
of keeping the quality

01:37:05.280 --> 01:37:08.890
of a public market as a place.

01:37:08.890 --> 01:37:09.390
Next.

01:37:12.940 --> 01:37:16.720
We'll go through a number
of diverse examples.

01:37:16.720 --> 01:37:23.260
Here is the apparatus for
achieving dual meaning.

01:37:23.260 --> 01:37:27.010
On the left is Church
Court at the intersection

01:37:27.010 --> 01:37:30.400
of Mass Avenue
and Beacon Street,

01:37:30.400 --> 01:37:36.010
where you can, in one
image next to each other,

01:37:36.010 --> 01:37:41.080
see the contemporary
housing and the old church.

01:37:41.080 --> 01:37:47.110
Remember my quotation from
Freud, that in spatial terms,

01:37:47.110 --> 01:37:51.400
you have to separate out images.

01:37:51.400 --> 01:37:54.490
You cannot have the same
content in one image.

01:37:54.490 --> 01:37:56.470
Here, they are separated out.

01:38:00.132 --> 01:38:03.610
The example on the right
is also from Boston.

01:38:03.610 --> 01:38:06.070
It's in Newton,
where a restaurant

01:38:06.070 --> 01:38:09.220
has taken over church.

01:38:09.220 --> 01:38:13.600
Churches are seen to be benign
institutions for accommodating

01:38:13.600 --> 01:38:17.200
new communal uses.

01:38:17.200 --> 01:38:20.440
We had a student here tried
to do the thesis in Toronto

01:38:20.440 --> 01:38:24.820
on taking a meat
abattoir building

01:38:24.820 --> 01:38:28.570
and turning it into
a housing, and trying

01:38:28.570 --> 01:38:30.760
to deal with the
stigma of making

01:38:30.760 --> 01:38:41.375
housing [INAUDIBLE] which
was considered unattractive.

01:38:41.375 --> 01:38:41.875
Next.

01:38:45.010 --> 01:38:49.000
An example of a significant
environmental Rouge plant

01:38:49.000 --> 01:38:52.990
in Detroit memorialized
in a number

01:38:52.990 --> 01:39:00.370
of ways by Sheeler's
photographs on the right--

01:39:00.370 --> 01:39:09.800
next-- by being the home of the
Model T, the first automobile.

01:39:09.800 --> 01:39:15.800
Also, the first workers strike
and the formation of a trade

01:39:15.800 --> 01:39:21.020
union, and an amplitude
of notions which

01:39:21.020 --> 01:39:23.210
should be memorialized.

01:39:23.210 --> 01:39:26.270
But the absence
of any Rouge plant

01:39:26.270 --> 01:39:29.820
is so large, that there's
nothing to be done.

01:39:29.820 --> 01:39:34.730
There's no use for the Rouge
plant in contemporary Detroit.

01:39:34.730 --> 01:39:40.010
So this is an example where
what should be memorialized

01:39:40.010 --> 01:39:42.930
is lost in the absence
of a new program.

01:39:47.920 --> 01:39:48.420
Next.

01:39:54.700 --> 01:39:58.960
This is the Bicocca
competition in Milano

01:39:58.960 --> 01:40:04.210
on the site of the large
Pirelli tire factory,

01:40:04.210 --> 01:40:11.470
which has moved out, leaving
a lot of infrastructure

01:40:11.470 --> 01:40:18.370
and a [INAUDIBLE] which
is subject to competition

01:40:18.370 --> 01:40:20.950
where almost all the leading
architects the world were

01:40:20.950 --> 01:40:26.510
invited to submit entries.

01:40:26.510 --> 01:40:30.940
I'm going to select two
entries to compare them.

01:40:30.940 --> 01:40:35.260
On the right is
Giancarlo De Carlo's On

01:40:35.260 --> 01:40:38.770
the left is the site plan.

01:40:38.770 --> 01:40:42.130
On the right is Giancarlo
De Carlo version.

01:40:42.130 --> 01:40:46.300
Using a large number of
the existing buildings,

01:40:46.300 --> 01:40:49.270
the whole idea is that
programmatically this

01:40:49.270 --> 01:40:55.030
would become, in Italian,
a new technological pole--

01:40:55.030 --> 01:40:59.530
P-O-L-E. It's only something
Italians can understand.

01:41:02.290 --> 01:41:08.170
What it's meant to be is some
kind of new electronic product

01:41:08.170 --> 01:41:12.160
management enterprise.

01:41:12.160 --> 01:41:16.885
Giancarlo uses a large number
of the existing streets

01:41:16.885 --> 01:41:24.140
and buildings, and introduces
new elements where needed.

01:41:24.140 --> 01:41:24.640
Next.

01:41:27.720 --> 01:41:32.010
Gabetti and Isola, a firm
of architects from Torino,

01:41:32.010 --> 01:41:35.520
came second in the
competition, do

01:41:35.520 --> 01:41:40.270
something which is interesting.

01:41:40.270 --> 01:41:46.740
They go back to find that
the Romans plow the land--

01:41:46.740 --> 01:41:54.540
organize the land in a
diagonal set of forms.

01:41:54.540 --> 01:42:01.830
And they start working
on this hidden geometry,

01:42:01.830 --> 01:42:06.330
and develop a plan based
upon the hidden geometry

01:42:06.330 --> 01:42:08.370
of the Roman land.

01:42:08.370 --> 01:42:08.870
Next.

01:42:12.460 --> 01:42:15.730
If they then
transfer their design

01:42:15.730 --> 01:42:20.650
into the world of ecology,
it's a green set of buildings.

01:42:24.640 --> 01:42:28.540
All of the notions
of other buildings

01:42:28.540 --> 01:42:32.990
should be environmentally
controlled and rationed

01:42:32.990 --> 01:42:36.340
and so on is part of the design.

01:42:36.340 --> 01:42:38.650
The issue that is
interesting here

01:42:38.650 --> 01:42:43.180
is, how do you connect
hidden references

01:42:43.180 --> 01:42:45.090
to existing conditions?

01:42:49.130 --> 01:42:53.270
Who would know the connection
between the Roman fields

01:42:53.270 --> 01:42:54.950
and the new buildings?

01:42:54.950 --> 01:42:56.100
How would you know that?

01:42:56.100 --> 01:42:58.010
How as an architect
do you make--

01:42:58.010 --> 01:43:03.500
you can put up a poster
or a bronze plaque

01:43:03.500 --> 01:43:04.400
telling the story?

01:43:04.400 --> 01:43:06.260
But you can't have
the two contents

01:43:06.260 --> 01:43:08.030
simultaneously available.

01:43:12.140 --> 01:43:16.700
We are encumbered, unlike Freud.

01:43:16.700 --> 01:43:18.740
According to Freud,
we as architects,

01:43:18.740 --> 01:43:20.600
who are spatialists,
are encumbered

01:43:20.600 --> 01:43:24.590
by not being able to
simultaneously produce

01:43:24.590 --> 01:43:32.145
an experience as presumably
you can in the human brain.

01:43:32.145 --> 01:43:32.645
Next.

01:43:35.310 --> 01:43:39.150
A similar stupid proposition.

01:43:39.150 --> 01:43:42.510
Not stupid proposition, but
more stupid than Gabetti

01:43:42.510 --> 01:43:44.670
and Isola's work.

01:43:44.670 --> 01:43:47.490
They actually are
very good architects.

01:43:47.490 --> 01:43:49.980
And I think in the
Bicocca competition,

01:43:49.980 --> 01:43:56.660
this is the most
interesting projection.

01:43:56.660 --> 01:44:00.370
This is from a studio
at the Harvard GSD.

01:44:00.370 --> 01:44:03.420
The site is Columbus.

01:44:03.420 --> 01:44:06.070
Where's Columbus, Ohio?

01:44:06.070 --> 01:44:06.570
Yes.

01:44:10.800 --> 01:44:14.755
This is where Eisenman is
going to build an art museum.

01:44:18.640 --> 01:44:21.340
He digs deep down
under the ground

01:44:21.340 --> 01:44:25.840
to find that this was an
Indian burial ground originally

01:44:25.840 --> 01:44:30.850
on which the Americans
built Camp Sherman, an army

01:44:30.850 --> 01:44:35.260
camp, on which the town
of Chillicothe was built.

01:44:35.260 --> 01:44:37.060
And now it's become Columbus.

01:44:37.060 --> 01:44:44.990
So there are four layers of
geometry, one above the other.

01:44:44.990 --> 01:44:51.850
So by the use of
the term scaling,

01:44:51.850 --> 01:44:56.830
he devises a method of
slowly retrieving the traces

01:44:56.830 --> 01:45:00.275
from underneath upwards.

01:45:00.275 --> 01:45:00.775
Next.

01:45:04.030 --> 01:45:10.930
Through a series of geometrical
moves to ultimately induce

01:45:10.930 --> 01:45:14.455
a solution for the museum.

01:45:17.050 --> 01:45:20.980
The problem again is the same
one as the Bicocca competition

01:45:20.980 --> 01:45:23.900
problem.

01:45:23.900 --> 01:45:29.510
What is the record of your
invention made public?

01:45:29.510 --> 01:45:32.960
How available is
the relationship

01:45:32.960 --> 01:45:37.950
between your final
product and your work?

01:45:37.950 --> 01:45:43.610
Who in heaven's name would
know the relationship

01:45:43.610 --> 01:45:47.300
as an outside experience?

01:45:47.300 --> 01:45:53.150
In any case, what is the point
of digging for inspiration

01:45:53.150 --> 01:45:55.890
under the ground when
you have [INAUDIBLE]

01:45:55.890 --> 01:45:59.150
atrophy of
conventional geometries

01:45:59.150 --> 01:46:02.000
to use for architecture?

01:46:02.000 --> 01:46:05.570
What is the advantage?

01:46:05.570 --> 01:46:08.070
It's a problematic question.

01:46:08.070 --> 01:46:10.940
Nobody at the GSD
asked the question.

01:46:10.940 --> 01:46:12.620
This became a wonderful game.

01:46:16.780 --> 01:46:20.080
There is no virgin
territory in this sense.

01:46:20.080 --> 01:46:24.220
Everything has an underneath
evocation of some use.

01:46:28.580 --> 01:46:31.220
It's landscape
urbanism penetrating

01:46:31.220 --> 01:46:33.740
beneath the skin
of the landscape

01:46:33.740 --> 01:46:40.205
into some territory, which is
enough to gestate new forms.

01:46:43.000 --> 01:46:43.500
Next.

01:46:46.662 --> 01:46:55.010
This [INAUDIBLE] work
on the grid of Chicago,

01:46:55.010 --> 01:46:58.690
producing this through a
series of exercises, scaling

01:46:58.690 --> 01:47:01.490
and transmission,
is equally stupid.

01:47:04.180 --> 01:47:05.110
Mixed.

01:47:05.110 --> 01:47:10.510
Not stupid-- intellectually
interesting, but so what.

01:47:13.490 --> 01:47:15.740
This is not a painting class.

01:47:20.820 --> 01:47:25.380
Do you need to know-- when
you look at a painting of Van

01:47:25.380 --> 01:47:31.290
Gogh's painted when he was in
asylum in the south of France,

01:47:31.290 --> 01:47:35.670
and he painted through a
particular window looking

01:47:35.670 --> 01:47:39.930
across the landscape, you
don't know this background.

01:47:39.930 --> 01:47:41.890
You just look at the painting.

01:47:41.890 --> 01:47:45.630
The painting has to
have enough in itself

01:47:45.630 --> 01:47:48.570
that the history is redundant.

01:47:48.570 --> 01:47:51.810
Who goes to an art
exhibition and demands

01:47:51.810 --> 01:47:57.280
that they understand the
history of each painting?

01:47:57.280 --> 01:48:04.650
How much of the history is part
of the experience of the art?

01:48:10.580 --> 01:48:11.750
I'm asking you a question.

01:48:11.750 --> 01:48:12.950
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:48:20.940 --> 01:48:25.835
You cannot really appreciate
a Japanese sword katana done

01:48:25.835 --> 01:48:30.955
by [INAUDIBLE] without knowing
the context in which it was

01:48:30.955 --> 01:48:31.455
made.

01:48:31.455 --> 01:48:33.290
JULIAN BEINART:
No, I understand.

01:48:33.290 --> 01:48:35.150
That's what we have museums for.

01:48:39.074 --> 01:48:40.352
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:48:40.352 --> 01:48:41.810
JULIAN BEINART: An
art production--

01:48:41.810 --> 01:48:46.580
sorry, an art production should
be able to stand on its own,

01:48:46.580 --> 01:48:51.560
independent of the knowledge
of the culture and so on.

01:48:54.930 --> 01:48:59.970
That's my own sense
of the capacity

01:48:59.970 --> 01:49:06.160
that we all have to
abstract from form ideas.

01:49:06.160 --> 01:49:08.080
AUDIENCE: Can you
explain different layers

01:49:08.080 --> 01:49:11.578
of meaning [INAUDIBLE]

01:49:11.578 --> 01:49:13.120
JULIAN BEINART: You
might-- now, as I

01:49:13.120 --> 01:49:17.110
said before, in looking
at a Van Gogh painting,

01:49:17.110 --> 01:49:19.780
you may well want to go
back to his drawings.

01:49:19.780 --> 01:49:22.810
You want to read his
letters to his brother.

01:49:22.810 --> 01:49:27.470
You want to understand his
epilepsy, and so on and so on.

01:49:27.470 --> 01:49:30.910
But essentially, given the
canvas in front of you,

01:49:30.910 --> 01:49:34.840
it should have enough content.

01:49:34.840 --> 01:49:41.260
You can increase the content,
but it cannot be totally

01:49:41.260 --> 01:49:49.060
dependent on your ability
to connect backwards.

01:49:49.060 --> 01:49:51.160
These examples we
just looked at,

01:49:51.160 --> 01:49:54.070
from Eisenman and
Gabetti and Isola,

01:49:54.070 --> 01:49:56.890
depend on your ability to--

01:49:56.890 --> 01:50:00.580
there's no evidence.

01:50:00.580 --> 01:50:03.010
Well, the new building
may be a consummate work

01:50:03.010 --> 01:50:08.650
of art, in which case reference
backward is immaterial.

01:50:08.650 --> 01:50:16.150
But as a device for
creating urbanism,

01:50:16.150 --> 01:50:17.950
it's a difficult argument.

01:50:17.950 --> 01:50:22.900
I'll concede the
difficulty of the argument.

01:50:22.900 --> 01:50:28.540
When Haydn uses the data
of his wife's birthday

01:50:28.540 --> 01:50:31.810
as the beginning
of some music, does

01:50:31.810 --> 01:50:36.880
the music quality
depend on you knowing

01:50:36.880 --> 01:50:39.730
that it was the
trivialization which

01:50:39.730 --> 01:50:42.010
caused him to write the music--

01:50:42.010 --> 01:50:45.670
a trivial beginning?

01:50:45.670 --> 01:50:52.450
I tend to argue in
favor of what you

01:50:52.450 --> 01:50:55.570
see being able to be
explained by what you see.

01:51:00.016 --> 01:51:04.520
AUDIENCE: Julian, we had in in
Politecnico di Milano an entire

01:51:04.520 --> 01:51:13.190
class for one year that was
about retracing the [INAUDIBLE]

01:51:13.190 --> 01:51:17.270
and then doing a project
[INAUDIBLE] But I would say,

01:51:17.270 --> 01:51:20.450
all my education in
Italy was-- like,

01:51:20.450 --> 01:51:27.800
urban design education was
strongly based on retracing

01:51:27.800 --> 01:51:36.150
former traces or ruins of
whatever was previously,

01:51:36.150 --> 01:51:41.700
and then integrating them into
the [INAUDIBLE] It was the word

01:51:41.700 --> 01:51:46.090
[INAUDIBLE] was
oriented towards--

01:51:46.090 --> 01:51:48.620
JULIAN BEINART: So it means
you can't build in America.

01:51:48.620 --> 01:51:52.890
AUDIENCE: It means that I felt
really lost when I came here,

01:51:52.890 --> 01:51:54.853
and then there was [INAUDIBLE].

01:51:54.853 --> 01:51:56.520
JULIAN BEINART: But
I'm just showing you

01:51:56.520 --> 01:52:01.150
that Eisenman found four
layers in Columbus, Ohio.

01:52:01.150 --> 01:52:01.860
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:52:04.600 --> 01:52:09.563
But it's-- yes,
[INAUDIBLE] like that.

01:52:09.563 --> 01:52:10.980
JULIAN BEINART:
There are no doubt

01:52:10.980 --> 01:52:15.870
instances where retrieving
ideas from the past

01:52:15.870 --> 01:52:20.610
is significant in
connecting you to something

01:52:20.610 --> 01:52:21.980
interesting about the future.

01:52:24.630 --> 01:52:25.935
This comes up very often.

01:52:25.935 --> 01:52:28.420
AUDIENCE: There shouldn't
be a restriction,

01:52:28.420 --> 01:52:33.020
because if you just need
to anchor it to the past,

01:52:33.020 --> 01:52:35.400
that means that there
is no room for a fully

01:52:35.400 --> 01:52:37.610
original idea from scratch.

01:52:37.610 --> 01:52:40.315
So it needn't be--

01:52:40.315 --> 01:52:43.920
[INAUDIBLE] to be
exclusive in nature.

01:52:43.920 --> 01:52:46.470
JULIAN BEINART: Well, I
wonder how many people

01:52:46.470 --> 01:52:49.260
have original ideas
from scratch, anyway.

01:52:49.260 --> 01:52:53.160
We all beleaguered by knowledge.

01:52:53.160 --> 01:52:56.670
Some is explicit, so is not.

01:52:56.670 --> 01:52:59.440
I don't know exactly
why I draw my hand,

01:52:59.440 --> 01:53:01.770
and draw in a particular way.

01:53:01.770 --> 01:53:04.050
Neither did Picasso.

01:53:04.050 --> 01:53:06.850
I mean, he drew in 70,000 ways.

01:53:06.850 --> 01:53:08.820
Sometimes, it's
clear [INAUDIBLE]

01:53:08.820 --> 01:53:12.390
art historians to show
what he was trying to do.

01:53:12.390 --> 01:53:21.520
Sometimes, he just draws with a
hidden vocabulary of knowledge.

01:53:21.520 --> 01:53:23.170
It's a contentious issue.

01:53:23.170 --> 01:53:27.790
All I'm trying to argue
is that these examples all

01:53:27.790 --> 01:53:33.250
try to connect you to
previous knowledge.

01:53:33.250 --> 01:53:36.790
AUDIENCE: Because of the
preservation that they want--

01:53:36.790 --> 01:53:39.870
it's all about preservation,
your view and your perspective

01:53:39.870 --> 01:53:42.355
on that, I guess.

01:53:42.355 --> 01:53:47.010
And I don't think during
our education in the US,

01:53:47.010 --> 01:53:49.160
we don't have so
much focus on that.

01:53:49.160 --> 01:53:50.800
JULIAN BEINART: No.

01:53:50.800 --> 01:53:52.990
Understandably, if
you grew up in Italy,

01:53:52.990 --> 01:53:58.240
it's a little difficult to
bypass the extraordinary things

01:53:58.240 --> 01:53:59.890
that have been done.

01:53:59.890 --> 01:54:03.100
If you grew up in
Greece, of course--

01:54:03.100 --> 01:54:08.440
Georgeas is not here today.

01:54:08.440 --> 01:54:09.610
He grew up in Greece.

01:54:09.610 --> 01:54:12.190
I wonder what you would
make of reconstructing

01:54:12.190 --> 01:54:19.780
the Agora as an item worth
generating a new vocabulary.

01:54:19.780 --> 01:54:22.910
Have you been to
the Agora in Athens?

01:54:22.910 --> 01:54:25.520
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:54:25.520 --> 01:54:26.750
JULIAN BEINART: Yeah.

01:54:26.750 --> 01:54:29.270
No, I'm thinking of
the Agora particularly,

01:54:29.270 --> 01:54:33.620
because it's such an
extraordinary difficult

01:54:33.620 --> 01:54:34.340
phenomenon--

01:54:34.340 --> 01:54:40.820
37 acres of land to invoke.

01:54:40.820 --> 01:54:48.620
The Romans-- [INAUDIBLE] was a
much easier literal formulation

01:54:48.620 --> 01:54:52.370
to seek adaptations from.

01:54:52.370 --> 01:54:55.430
The Greeks didn't
believe in the cardinal.

01:54:55.430 --> 01:55:00.530
There is no cardinality in
the Agora in Athens There

01:55:00.530 --> 01:55:04.580
no organization based upon
a simple precept, such

01:55:04.580 --> 01:55:08.360
as you need a horizontal line
and a vertical line to cross.

01:55:12.990 --> 01:55:14.850
This is complex
territory, and I'm

01:55:14.850 --> 01:55:18.660
not enough of an art historian
to take this further.

01:55:18.660 --> 01:55:20.130
Let's move to Leon Krier.

01:55:23.090 --> 01:55:30.740
First of all, there is stupid
distinction between res privata

01:55:30.740 --> 01:55:32.900
and res publica.

01:55:32.900 --> 01:55:34.760
In the next class,
which we'll do

01:55:34.760 --> 01:55:38.660
in this start in the second
half after these pictures,

01:55:38.660 --> 01:55:45.980
I'll try to show you how
inappropriate this distinction

01:55:45.980 --> 01:55:47.000
is.

01:55:47.000 --> 01:55:52.820
For him, a good city is one
in which the public domain is

01:55:52.820 --> 01:55:57.770
evidenced through a series
of architectural forms

01:55:57.770 --> 01:56:00.890
which deviate really
from classical form,

01:56:00.890 --> 01:56:04.160
or deviate, which are
determined by their allegiance

01:56:04.160 --> 01:56:05.790
to classical form.

01:56:05.790 --> 01:56:06.290
Next.

01:56:09.760 --> 01:56:15.490
The world of the private are
really rectangular boxes.

01:56:15.490 --> 01:56:18.850
A good city is
one which combines

01:56:18.850 --> 01:56:24.880
the two, in which the public
is signally differentiated

01:56:24.880 --> 01:56:25.600
from the private.

01:56:28.370 --> 01:56:30.830
What happens if you
are wealthy and you

01:56:30.830 --> 01:56:37.680
want to put a classical arch
in the front of your house,

01:56:37.680 --> 01:56:38.910
I don't know.

01:56:38.910 --> 01:56:41.380
But let's leave that example.

01:56:41.380 --> 01:56:41.880
Next.

01:56:44.862 --> 01:56:51.570
The use of classicism in this
project of his for an island

01:56:51.570 --> 01:56:57.390
resort off the coast of Africa.

01:56:57.390 --> 01:57:03.600
It aims to recreate
a context borrowed

01:57:03.600 --> 01:57:05.580
from a significant past.

01:57:09.700 --> 01:57:13.080
It may be exotic enough
to attract people

01:57:13.080 --> 01:57:18.180
looking for another
experience in life, even

01:57:18.180 --> 01:57:29.220
if it's quixotic and veneer
and lacking in originality.

01:57:29.220 --> 01:57:33.750
But then, who cares what
the original consequence

01:57:33.750 --> 01:57:36.060
of classical architecture was?

01:57:38.350 --> 01:57:38.850
Next.

01:57:42.810 --> 01:57:46.530
When it's taken seriously,
such as by Prince Charles

01:57:46.530 --> 01:57:49.500
and his confreres
in England, you

01:57:49.500 --> 01:57:54.290
see a political
argument made in favor

01:57:54.290 --> 01:58:00.750
of Canaletto's version of London
and what London has become.

01:58:00.750 --> 01:58:02.640
According to Prince
Charles, London

01:58:02.640 --> 01:58:05.980
has been brutalized by
modern architecture.

01:58:05.980 --> 01:58:06.480
Next.

01:58:09.850 --> 01:58:13.360
So Richmond Terrace on
the left on the Thames

01:58:13.360 --> 01:58:18.490
is an office complex designed
by Quinlan Terry, who

01:58:18.490 --> 01:58:22.240
works with classical
architecture, as opposed

01:58:22.240 --> 01:58:29.020
to these ugly buildings,
which the Prince assigns

01:58:29.020 --> 01:58:32.200
to modern architecture.

01:58:32.200 --> 01:58:41.350
So here is the attempt to use
an architectural form, derived

01:58:41.350 --> 01:58:45.700
from classicism quite
freely, to maintain

01:58:45.700 --> 01:58:52.820
a certain civility of form
and a certain expression,

01:58:52.820 --> 01:58:56.020
which is universally
admired and understood,

01:58:56.020 --> 01:58:58.460
instead of the
arbitrary selections

01:58:58.460 --> 01:59:00.740
of form under modernism.

01:59:00.740 --> 01:59:01.240
Next.

01:59:07.170 --> 01:59:13.980
In the Holocaust
Museum in Washington,

01:59:13.980 --> 01:59:17.340
the architect says that
he wishes to excavate

01:59:17.340 --> 01:59:20.070
memory instead of history.

01:59:20.070 --> 01:59:25.170
So he makes the intellectual
leap, or the artistic leap,

01:59:25.170 --> 01:59:30.870
by taking forms which
emanate from Auschwitz,

01:59:30.870 --> 01:59:34.200
and introducing them into
the vocabulary of forms

01:59:34.200 --> 01:59:36.630
that he uses in the Holocause--

01:59:36.630 --> 01:59:42.950
bricks, steel, triangular
metal sections.

01:59:42.950 --> 01:59:43.450
Next.

01:59:53.130 --> 01:59:57.780
In keeping with
Washingtonian urbanism,

01:59:57.780 --> 02:00:02.940
the interior of the
building is exotic.

02:00:02.940 --> 02:00:07.200
The performance of the
building as it faces the public

02:00:07.200 --> 02:00:07.810
is quiet.

02:00:10.960 --> 02:00:11.460
Next.

02:00:15.660 --> 02:00:21.840
Similarly, on the left is a plan
by a Dutch landscape architect

02:00:21.840 --> 02:00:25.230
of, up above, field patterns.

02:00:25.230 --> 02:00:29.640
Below is a housing project
based on the field patterns

02:00:29.640 --> 02:00:33.390
of the previous agriculture.

02:00:33.390 --> 02:00:38.180
And on the right is a
house in Switzerland

02:00:38.180 --> 02:00:46.160
by Mario Botta, who says,
"I'm obliged to build

02:00:46.160 --> 02:00:50.060
a building in suburbia and
isolate the building, which

02:00:50.060 --> 02:00:51.460
I don't like.

02:00:51.460 --> 02:00:53.790
I'm going to do it,
but at the same time,

02:00:53.790 --> 02:00:57.800
I'm going to deviate its form
so significantly that it's

02:00:57.800 --> 02:01:00.560
a different product altogether."

02:01:00.560 --> 02:01:05.990
So here is the
argument on the left

02:01:05.990 --> 02:01:16.280
that there's enough trace
again for you to impose on it

02:01:16.280 --> 02:01:19.880
an argument of consonance.

02:01:19.880 --> 02:01:25.730
On the right is an acceptance
of a certain spatial vocabulary,

02:01:25.730 --> 02:01:32.060
but then in particular denying
the vocabulary by making it

02:01:32.060 --> 02:01:32.970
round.

02:01:32.970 --> 02:01:33.470
Next.

02:01:38.240 --> 02:01:42.350
Here is a simple example.

02:01:42.350 --> 02:01:46.880
In Groningen, in
Holland, a library

02:01:46.880 --> 02:01:50.450
is extended by building
it as exactly--

02:01:50.450 --> 02:01:54.260
building two new
arms of it parallel

02:01:54.260 --> 02:01:56.210
to the existing building.

02:01:56.210 --> 02:01:59.325
There's no question but
that they should look like.

02:01:59.325 --> 02:01:59.825
Next.

02:02:03.210 --> 02:02:10.170
And lastly, a few
ideas from Washington.

02:02:10.170 --> 02:02:22.130
Washington's plan made
selecting site for monument

02:02:22.130 --> 02:02:28.035
and the maintenance of memory
through monument quite easy.

02:02:28.035 --> 02:02:28.535
Next.

02:02:33.890 --> 02:02:37.370
Let's jump to the
contemporary problem.

02:02:37.370 --> 02:02:39.020
These are two.

02:02:39.020 --> 02:02:49.220
On the left is the first attempt
to design the FDR Memorial.

02:02:49.220 --> 02:02:56.870
These panels of stone are taller
than the Washington Monument.

02:02:56.870 --> 02:02:59.730
The family objects.

02:02:59.730 --> 02:03:02.420
Another architect is
brought in to reduce

02:03:02.420 --> 02:03:06.540
the height of the panels
down to a smaller level.

02:03:06.540 --> 02:03:07.040
Next.

02:03:10.970 --> 02:03:16.010
The last outcome was the attempt
to leave architecture alone

02:03:16.010 --> 02:03:22.640
and to use a garden as
the appropriate memorial.

02:03:22.640 --> 02:03:27.590
Now, this is either because
contemporary architecture

02:03:27.590 --> 02:03:30.560
has no way of doing memorials.

02:03:35.370 --> 02:03:37.810
Do you know Frank
Geary's proposition

02:03:37.810 --> 02:03:41.170
for the Eisenhower Memorial?

02:03:41.170 --> 02:03:44.380
Has anybody seen it?

02:03:44.380 --> 02:03:48.220
It's under grave
discussion at the moment

02:03:48.220 --> 02:03:51.010
as to whether it's
acceptable or not.

02:03:51.010 --> 02:03:56.320
It has none of Geary's formal
language of architecture

02:03:56.320 --> 02:03:58.340
as embedded in the project.

02:04:04.490 --> 02:04:09.850
This is a case where nature
is seen as invariably benign.

02:04:12.790 --> 02:04:16.870
If you can't do a man-made
manifestation of something,

02:04:16.870 --> 02:04:20.195
you rely on nature
to do it for you.

02:04:20.195 --> 02:04:20.695
Next.

02:04:27.060 --> 02:04:30.270
This is a late 19th
century attempt

02:04:30.270 --> 02:04:48.630
to cover the existing obelisk
with an armature which renders

02:04:48.630 --> 02:04:52.980
it more publicly acceptable.

02:04:52.980 --> 02:04:59.880
It's probably the
finiteness of a monument.

02:04:59.880 --> 02:05:04.890
The obelisk is, after all,
a very elementary geometry,

02:05:04.890 --> 02:05:08.700
which needs to be denied
by those who need to give

02:05:08.700 --> 02:05:11.220
it more appropriate meaning.

02:05:11.220 --> 02:05:13.260
The same thing on the right.

02:05:13.260 --> 02:05:17.730
This is Ross Perot's addition
to the Vietnam Memorial.

02:05:17.730 --> 02:05:21.630
Maya Lin's memorial
is absently abstract.

02:05:21.630 --> 02:05:27.060
It has only vertical
planes with names on it.

02:05:27.060 --> 02:05:30.810
In order to render
it more acceptable,

02:05:30.810 --> 02:05:39.600
we get the addition of this
example of human soldiers.

02:05:39.600 --> 02:05:40.950
No women, of course.

02:05:43.520 --> 02:05:49.150
The abstraction allows
almost everybody

02:05:49.150 --> 02:06:01.250
to take part in it, whereas once
you express particularities,

02:06:01.250 --> 02:06:06.770
you have the problem of what
particularities to choose.

02:06:06.770 --> 02:06:10.700
An obelisk is universal.

02:06:10.700 --> 02:06:14.480
A decorated obelisk
means that somebody

02:06:14.480 --> 02:06:19.260
had to make decisions about what
is the appropriate decoration.

02:06:19.260 --> 02:06:19.760
Next.

02:06:23.130 --> 02:06:27.030
And two last examples of
a contemporary monument

02:06:27.030 --> 02:06:33.930
are expressions of the need to
retain memory about something.

02:06:33.930 --> 02:06:39.780
On the left is the Navy
Memorial in Washington.

02:06:39.780 --> 02:06:43.920
It's a developer project which
has left a space in front,

02:06:43.920 --> 02:06:48.960
a circular space with a single
figure of a soldier that

02:06:48.960 --> 02:06:50.670
is the Navy sailor.

02:06:50.670 --> 02:06:56.010
It's a male again-- white
male, on top of the world.

02:06:56.010 --> 02:07:00.420
But at the same time, you
enter a door to the right,

02:07:00.420 --> 02:07:03.480
and you go inside
this interior space,

02:07:03.480 --> 02:07:07.290
where you can see a movie about
the wonder of the United States

02:07:07.290 --> 02:07:08.110
Navy.

02:07:08.110 --> 02:07:10.110
And there's also
a computer which

02:07:10.110 --> 02:07:14.520
will show your grandchild
how wonderful you were

02:07:14.520 --> 02:07:17.760
when you were a young sailor.

02:07:17.760 --> 02:07:19.530
Next.

02:07:19.530 --> 02:07:22.775
The Air Force Memorial
tried to do the same thing.

02:07:22.775 --> 02:07:26.460
Here is the first project
for the Air Force Memorial.

02:07:26.460 --> 02:07:30.000
It sits on a plinth,
which is the updated

02:07:30.000 --> 02:07:34.860
version of the world on top of
a symbolic representation, which

02:07:34.860 --> 02:07:38.010
is fixed.

02:07:38.010 --> 02:07:42.450
Here, you have a
combination of the idea

02:07:42.450 --> 02:07:48.400
that the memorial, which is
only fixed and not updatable,

02:07:48.400 --> 02:07:55.030
needs to have an updating system
as a part of a binary system--

02:07:55.030 --> 02:08:01.750
one perpetual one
updated contemporary.

02:08:08.240 --> 02:08:12.170
I think these two are
examples of a kind of move

02:08:12.170 --> 02:08:21.260
to democratize or bring
architectural form

02:08:21.260 --> 02:08:26.610
into everyday existence.

02:08:26.610 --> 02:08:29.040
I don't know how
successful these will be.

02:08:33.580 --> 02:08:35.770
Next.

02:08:35.770 --> 02:08:40.090
It's the [INAUDIBLE] OK, we've
gone through a whole series

02:08:40.090 --> 02:08:44.020
of examples of issues.